<FIRST>r w PM-Fitzwater-Gorbachev     12-05 0135</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fitzwater-Gorbachev,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fitzwater, Gorbachev Have Weighty Discussion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev had a direct question at
the superpower summit for President Bush's press secretary, Marlin
Fitzwater, who had derided the Soviet leader earlier this year as a
``drugstore cowboy.''
   ``Marlin, you lose 30 pounds?'' Gorbachev asked the once-stout
Fitzwater.
   There was no mention of the earlier jibe, which had been
intended to question Gorbachev's sincerity about arms-control
proposals.
   Instead, they talked about the liquid diet by which Fitzwater
has lost 35 pounds, dropping to 198 pounds.
   ``That's good,'' Gorbachev said.
   Pleased that the weight loss was noticed, Fitzwater thanked the
Soviet leader.
   Fitzwater gave reporters the account of the conversation with
Gorbachev aboard the Soviet cruise liner Maxim Gorky in Malta's
Marsaxlokk Bay, where Gorbachev and Bush held two days of talks.
</TEXT>
