<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 0109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Turner'sNeighbors     12-05 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turner's Neighbors,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ted Turner's Neighbors Want Electricity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPPS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five families who live without electricity
near Ted Turner's 8,100-acre plantation say they want the
broadcasting executive to allow power lines to cross his property
to their homes.
   Dressie Sloan, with the Jefferson County National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People, accused Turner of trying to
get rid of his poor neighbors by refusing to extend the electric
lines.
   ``One word from Mr. Turner, and they'd have their lights,''
Sloan told the Tallahassee Democrat Sunday. ``He has the power and
the money to do it, but he wants to squeeze them out.''
   But Avalon Plantation manager George Purvis said Turner was only
complying with a former owner's restrictions.
   ``Mr. Turner has never tried to get those people to move out,''
Purvis told the newspaper. ``But Mrs. (Alexandra) McKay thought an
above-ground wire would destroy the national beauty of her land.''
   Dee Woods, Turner's personal assistant in Atlanta, said he was
unavailable to answer Sloan's complaint.
   About a mile through the woods from the plantation, Frances
Oliver has lived in one of the three tarpaper-covered shacks for 30
years.
   ``We used to have a school out here, a church and maybe a couple
hundred people,'' she said. About a dozen people now live on almost
215 acres surrounded by tree farms, hunting clubs and plantation
forest.
   Ms. Oliver said she relies on a wood stove for cooking and
heating. She totes water from a plantation well and reads by a
kerosene lamp. Car batteries run her TV set.
   Electricity would be nice, Ms. Oliver said. ``Maybe it would
bring the people back,'' she said.
   But even if Turner did approve the extension, Purvis said he
wondered who would foot the bill. A power line from the
plantation's terminal to the houses would cost at least $40,000,
according to Ronald Bass, a manager for Tri-County Electric
Cooperative.
   State law gives people the right to draw power from a utility
company, but since Tri-County is a rural co-op it operates under
federal guidelines, and does not have to install the lines free of
charge.
</TEXT>
