<DOCNO> AP891205-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 0205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-PeaceDividend     12-05 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Peace Dividend,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Budget Writers Wary of `Peace Dividend'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top Democratic congressional budget writers
agree with President Bush's warning that a proposed trimming of the
Pentagon's budget won't produce a ``peace dividend'' for domestic
programs.
   Liberals and other lawmakers hope the easing of Cold War
tensions will translate into a siphoning of defense money into
health, education, transportation and other domestic needs.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney is studying plans to pare up to
$180 billion from anticipated military spending increases through
1994. The administration says it's still trying to decide what the
size and shape of the cuts will be.
   But the chairmen of Congress' two budget committees expressed
caution Monday for those who hope the reductions will mean a
windfall for other government initiatives.
   Senate Budget Committee Chairman James Sasser, D-Tenn., said his
analysis of defense reductions under study by the administration is
that savings of just $2 billion are likely next year.
   Over five years, military spending would still increase by $200
billion, excluding the effects of inflation, he said.
   ``Clearly, there is no so-called peace dividend,'' said Sasser,
whose figures were based on Pentagon plans and economic projections
announced earlier this year.
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House Budget
Committee, said there are still too many unknowns to predict
whether domestic programs will benefit from defense cuts Bush is
expected to propose.
   Panetta said there are questions about the types of savings he
will seek, whether aid will be sought to offset economic
dislocations caused by closed bases and weapons plants, and how
much of the cutbacks would go to deficit reduction.
   ``I have always been very cautious about arguing for a defense
dividend,'' he said.
   Liberal lawmakers argue that with better U.S.-Soviet relations,
it's time to shrink the defense budget, which comprises about
one-fourth of the government's $1.2 trillion annual spending.
   ``The more you cut from the military, the less damage you do to
domestic programs to meet Gramm-Rudman targets,'' Rep. Barney
Frank, D-Mass., said Monday.
   Frank has been a leader of a group of liberals pressing
congressional leaders to slash about $20 billion from the Pentagon
budget and redistribute most of it among health, housing, education
and other domestic programs.
   Bush, speaking Monday to reporters at a Brussels, Belgium, news
conference after his summit with Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, tried to douse those hopes.
   ``We have a lot of demands at home, and there's no question
about that,'' Bush said. ``But I think it is premature to speak as
some are at home about a peace dividend _ take a lot of money out
of defense and put it into other worthy causes.''
   The president cited the problems the government will have in
scraping together enough savings to meet the Gramm-Rudman
deficit-reduction law's requirement of a fiscal 1991 shortfall of
no more than $64 billion.
   The administration is expected to forecast a deficit for fiscal
1990, which ends Sept. 30, of about $110 billion. Bush will submit
his proposed 1991 budget to Congress on Jan. 22.
   ``There just isn't a lot of, quote, excess money, unquote,
floating around there,'' Bush said.
   The cuts Cheney is considering would be made from increases
already projected. Thus, rather than reducing military spending
totals, they are widely expected on Capitol Hill to leave Defense
Department outlays near the current level of about $290 billion.
   Since 1986, military spending has decreased by an average of 3
percent annually when inflation is taken into account, even though
the actual amount going to the Pentagon has increased each year.
Defense Department outlays, $265 billion in 1986, should reach $287
billion this year.
   Defense spending is difficult to shrink quickly because much of
it _ such as purchases of fleets of jet fighters _ is committed in
contracts that span several years. Even reducing numbers of troops
has offsetting costs, such as higher civilian unemployment rates.
   The conventional wisdom among lawmakers and lobbyists is that
the 1991 Defense Department budget is unlikely to contain
reductions of more than $3 billion to $8 billion from the increases
that were already planned for the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
