<FIRST>r a PM-HealthySoulFood Bjt   12-05 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Healthy Soul Food, Bjt,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Restaurant Owner Removes the Fat But Not the Soul from Menu</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At Army &amp; Lou's, one of the nation's most elegant
purveyors of black American cuisine, the owner is working to lower
cholesterol _ showing that soul food doesn't have to be hard on the
heart.
   ``A lot of people cannot imagine soul food without using lard,
heavy fat and grease, but people are very health-conscious today,''
said owner Avis Piper, who supervises the kitchen and occasionally
helps cook.
   ``We're making a statement that soul food doesn't have to have
fat, or oil or cholesterol to be soul food and to be healthy food.''
   On a recent Saturday night, patrons at the 200-seat restaurant
included many of Chicago's leading black officials: a U.S.
congressman, the county prosecutor and four state lawmakers.
   The South Side business also is frequented by black and white
celebrities such as Bill Cosby and the cast of his TV family, the
Rev. Jesse Jackson and U.S. Sen. Paul Simon.
   The menu, with more than 100 items, runs the gamut from
black-eyed peas and ham hocks at $7 to filet mignon and lobster
tails at $35.
   The meats mostly are lean. Vegetables are steamed rather than
fried or boiled. Entries like the sweet-potato pie and salmon
croquettes are cholesterol-free.
   No salt, artificial flavorings or additives are used, and
vegetable shortening is substituted for lard in cooking.
   Mrs. Piper says the low-cholesterol dishes offer some customers
more of a choice. Dempsey Travis, a prominent black real estate
developer and writer, is one who's hooked.
   ``There are certain things like catfish I wouldn't eat, but now
I find it highly desirable and delicate,'' said Travis, who eats at
the restaurant at least twice a week. ``It's just the kind of place
you're proud to take a person,'' he said.
   The restaurant was founded in 1945 by William Armstrong, whose
nickname was Army, and his wife Luvilla, known as Lou. The two ran
it for 28 years before selling to another couple.
   Mrs. Piper, a former public school teacher and interior
designer, and her husband, Benjamin, an accountant, were regular
patrons before buying the restaurant 15 months ago.
   Mrs. Piper, who had been an amateur gourmet cook, says she hopes
the restaurant will help set a trend toward healthier soul food.
   Dr. Linda Van Horn, a registered dietician at the Northwestern
University Medical School, says that's a welcome change.
   ``It's well-known that the black population has a higher risk
for heart disease, stroke, hypertension and diabetes than the white
population because of diet and other factors,'' she said.
   ``Hopefully, the risks can be reduced without altering the
flavor that people love,'' she said.
</TEXT>
