<DOCNO> AP891205-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 0300EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneStrike     12-05 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Strike,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Return to Jobs, Telephone Company Tackles Backlog</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Telephone workers returning to work after a
14-week strike faced a huge backlog of requests for installation,
service and other work.
   ``Everybody's now back to work. We are delighted to see them
all. The priority is attacking this backlog,'' Nynex Corp.
spokesman John Bonomo said Monday.
   The strike by about 40,000 members of the Communications Workers
of America, employed by Nynex subsidiary New York Telephone, and
20,000 members of the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers, at New England Telephone, affected 10 million customers.
   It began Aug. 6 and was the last of four regional phone company
strikes to be resolved. The IBEW and New England Telephone did not
settle until Nov. 20. The CWA ratified its contract Friday.
   New York Telephone said it was trying to fill more than 100,000
service orders and a potential backlog of another 150,000
installations with customers who withheld orders during the work
stoppage.
   Filling those orders will take until May, the company said.
Repair work, it said, is up to date.
   During the strike, some 10,000 managers filled in for striking
workers. One striker was killed in a strike-related car accident,
and Nynex claimed hundreds of acts of sabotage were made against
its property.
   A major sticking point was a proposal by the company that
workers share the cost of health care. Nynex conceded this point in
exchange for reduced wage increases.
</TEXT>
