<FIRST>r a PM-MultipleTransplant     12-05 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Multiple Transplant,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Improving Following Multi-Organ Transplant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With his wife showing signs of progress after
the world's first heart, liver and kidney transplant, John Martin
was on the telephone in a delicate conversation. On the line was
the husband of the donor.
   The talk was brief, said Dimitri Mavris, whose wife, 26-year-old
Auli, died from injuries suffered in a freak automobile accident.
Auli Mavris' organs were transplanted into 26-year-old Cindy Martin
in Pittsburgh on Monday.
   ``He said, `You have given us a great gift,' and I said, `She
would have wanted it that way. Our prayers are with you and your
wife,''' Mavris said.
   Mrs. Mavris was killed after being struck by a car driven by a
neighbor in a parking lot by her apartment in Atlanta, when she was
taking a load of trash to a bin.
   Mrs. Martin remained in critical condition, considered normal
after transplant surgery, in Presbyterian-University Hospital's
intensive care unit. Doctors said Monday they were encouraged by
her progress and planned to wean her from a respirator. They said
infection had become her greatest risk.
   ``Hopefully, she will go home in three or four weeks,'' said Dr.
John Armitage, who performed the heart transplant. ``Right now her
organ function looks encouraging. She's awake and writing us
notes.''
   Although multi-organ transplants have been done before, this was
the first involving the heart, liver and a kidney, Armitage said.
   Three other people have received combination heart-liver
transplants, but only Stormie Jones, a 12-year-old Texas girl who
received her new organs in February 1984, has survived the
procedure.
   The 21{-hour operation, which ended at 5 p.m. Sunday, was broken
into three parts, with the heart transplanted first, the liver
second and the kidney last.
   ``Her greatest need was for improved circulation and treatment
of her failed heart. That was addressed first,'' Armitage said.
``Her kidneys, although bad, were the least of her multi-organ
system failure.''
   In Chicago, the recipient of the nation's first living-donor
liver transplant, 22-month-old Alyssa Smith, was in serious but
stable condition, University of Chicago Hospitals spokeswoman Mary
Fetsch said today. Doctors are pleased with her progress eight days
after the procedure, the spokeswoman said. She has been moved out
of intensive care to a private room and shows no signs of rejecting
the liver.
   Her mother, Teresa, who donated a piece of her liver for the
operation, was in good condition and expected to be released from
the hospital this week, Ms. Fetsch said.
   Mrs. Martin suffers from familial cardiomyopathy, an inherited
heart disease. Her father died when he was 31 and many relatives on
his side of the family have died young, Martin said.
   On Oct. 20, 1985, one day after the couple were married, Mrs.
Martin was admitted to Presbyterian-University Hospital to await
her first heart transplant. She received it Nov. 6.
   Since then, she has suffered from chronic rejection of the heart
and developed hepatits and kidney dysfunction.
   Martin, 28, said at a news conference that he's been telling his
wife ``to hang in there and hope that our lives are finally going
to turn around.''
   Mrs. Martin had to give up her secretarial job and has spent
most of her time at home in Archbald doing only light household
chores, because she tired easily and developed several infections,
said her husband, a manufacturing engineer.
   Armitage said ethical questions of retransplantation, despite
the shortage of donor organs, ``was not a major consideration'' in
Mrs. Martin's case.
   ``She is a very young patient,'' he said. ``We were very
committed to her.''
</TEXT>
