<FIRST>r a PM-AmishNewspaper     12-05 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Amish Newspaper,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amish Newspaper Celebrates 100th Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER C. KENT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SUGARCREEK, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only newspaper of the Amish and
Mennonites is owned by a Jewish family, edited by a Lutheran and
has its readers double as unpaid reporters.
   Butter churning, recipes and buggy accidents are among the
subjects that fill the pages of The Budget, which is gearing up for
its 100th anniversary as what may be the most widely circulated
small-town newspaper in the country.
   George Smith, 82, has worked at the newspaper in this Tuscarawas
County village of 2,000 in eastern Ohio since his father bought the
paper in 1920. There are no Amish and two Mennonites on the staff.
   ``One problem with Amish girls is they work a couple of years
then get married,'' said Smith. As for the Amish men: ``It's not
their kind of work.''
   Smith supervises the 600 or so ``scribes'' who send in
handwritten items of parochial interest from Amish and Mennonite
settlements in such places as Charm, Ohio; Macon, Miss.; Sarasota,
Fla.; and Intercourse, Pa. Smith, whose title is associate editor _
although there is no editor _ also lays out the pages.
   Smith, who became editor and publisher in 1936, sold the paper
to two employees in 1974. When they left, Albert Spector of Wooster
bought the paper in 1981.
   Spector, who is Jewish, owns Spector's stores, a major
advertiser in The Budget and supplier of dry goods to the Amish and
Mennonites.
   Every week the paper receives as many as 400 letters from the
scattered communities describing births, marriages, buggy accidents
and the weather.
   There are two editions, one serving Sugarcreek and surrounding
areas and the national edition, which carries more than 300 letters
from Plain People settlements in the lower 48 states and more than
a dozen foreign countries.
   A special 100th anniversary edition will be sent to The Budget's
18,000 subscribers in May. Smith is planning a summer party for all
his correspondents.
   Smith said he edits the letters for spelling, punctuation and
clarity, but ``we like to keep the flavor.''
   For instance, an Amish from Stockport, Ohio, had this
butter-churning tale: ``Floyd Beechy rigged a plastic crate on the
center of the buggy wheel. In this he fastened a plastic jug of
cream. As he or the Mrs. had to drive the scholars to school every
day, this saved churning at home. Now they have 2 girls at home and
probably don't churn anymore.''
   From Guys Mills, Pa.: ``James A. Miller is laid up with a torn
ligament in back of his leg and internal bleeding. This happened
while chasing heifers.''
   And from Jamesport, Mo.: ``It seems the postal service is
getting slack again. For quite awhile we received The Budget on
Sat., but lately it doesn't come till Mon.''
   Reports of violent crime are rare because occurrences are rare,
Smith said.
   ``We try to avoid anything about crime. We don't feel it has a
place in The Budget ... unless it really directly involves the
Amish.''
   The paper has grown from four pages to 30 or more since its
first edition and production has been modernized. The Budget is now
on its third computer system, complete with laser printer, and some
Mennonite letters arrive by fax.
   The Budget scribes are not paid. But good writers receive
stamped envelopes to mail in stories. If they're really good, they
get free subscriptions.
   There are no photographs in the national edition, as the Amish
shun having their pictures taken. Recipes as well as display and
classified ads are included.
   Surgarcreek is surrounded by the largest settlement of Amish in
the world, with 20,000 to 25,000 living in Holmes, Wayne, Coshoctan
and Tuscarawas counties in Ohio. About 100,000 Amish people live in
the United States. Figures on the Mennonite population were
unavailable.
</TEXT>
