<FIRST>r i PM-Australia-Smoking     12-05 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Australia-Smoking,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government To Ban Tobacco Ads In Print Media</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Dollar amounts U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Government today said it
plans to outlaw cigarette advertising in the print media in an
attempt to slash the $2 billion a year spent on health care for
smokers.
   ``It reflects the concern that tobacco consumption is the major
preventable cause of illness in the Australian community today,''
Health Minister Neal Blewett said in announcing the decision.
   ``The Government has a clear responsibility to act to discourage
Australians from smoking and particularly to reduce pressures on
young people to take up smoking.''
   Advertising of tobacco products has been banned in the
electronic media since 1976.
   Blewett said the government would amend the Smoking and Tobacco
Products Advertisements Bill to legislate the ban on advertising in
newspapers and magazines.
   He said there was sufficient evidence of a link between tobacco
advertising and the taking up of smoking to justify the
government's decision on strong public health grounds.
   ``Although advertising is not the only determinant in people's
decision to smoke, research has established that it does affect and
reinforce other influences such as peer and social pressures,''
Blewett said.
   The ban will bring Australia into line with many other countries
that have outlawed tobacco advertising, including Canada, Norway,
Finland, Italy, Portugal, Singapore and Iceland.
   Blewett noted that research in Norway had shown ``substantial
falls'' in smoking among adolescents since a ban took effect in
that country in 1975.
   Sports Minister Graham Richardson said earlier he opposed a
total ban on tobacco advertising because some sports relied heavily
on tobacco sponsorship.
   He said that sport received about $16 million a year from
tobacco companies in Australia and that replacement sponsorships of
that size would be difficult.
</TEXT>
