<FIRST>r w PM-Barry-Drugs     12-05 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barry-Drugs,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Police Satisfied With Handling of Mayor's Drug Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia police department has
concluded its officers acted properly in handling allegations that
Mayor Marion Barry was hospitalized for a drug overdose six years
ago, a newspaper reported today.
   Police Chief Isaac Fulwood believes the department and
then-chief Maurice Turner were right to drop the matter after the
allegation could not be corroborated, sources told The Washington
Post.
   A Howard University psychiatrist reportedly told police
investigators in 1984 that the mayor suffered from a drug overdose
in 1983.
   Barry, in an effort Monday to quell the overdose allegations,
let reporters review 154 pages of medical records. But the records
were withdrawn after an hour and many reporters complained it was
impossible to draw conclusions from them.
   Barry's spokeswoman said the records were released to
substantiate the mayor's statements that he suffered from a hiatal
hernia in 1983 and not a cocaine overdose.
   The records indicated that doctors diagnosed Barry's illness as
a hiatal hernia, an abnormality of the digestive tract that can
cause symptoms similar to those of a heart attack.
   None of the records showed that Barry was tested for the
presence of cocaine or that illegal drugs caused his
hospitalization.
   Medical experts told the Post the symptoms identified in Barry's
records were consistent with several illnesses, including a hiatal
hernia, heart disease and a cocaine overdose.
</TEXT>
