<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     12-05 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0595</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Rain Turns to Snow in Pacific Northwest ^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was turning to snow today in the wind-lashed Pacific
Northwest as cold lashed much of the eastern part of the country.
   Strong winds pounded the eastern slopes of Montana's Rockies
with gusts of up to 64 mph at Livingston, Mont. Up to a foot of
snow was forecast for western Montana.
   A cold front brought steady rain in the northern Pacific Coast
region Monday afternoon. Rainshowers extended across the Northern
Plateau into the northern Rocky Mountain region.
   Temperatures were below freezing all day Monday from the Great
Lakes to the northern Atlantic Coast, with highs in the teens in
northern New England.
   Philadelphia shivered under a low of 18 Monday and a wind chill
of down to minus 25.
   Monday's low of 15 degrees recorded at Newark International
Airport was far below the normal low of 32, said Harry Woodworth, a
National Weather Service meteorologist.
   ``You don't need any detailed descriptions of it out there,''
Woodworth said. ``It's cold. Period.''
   Clouds hung over much of the northern half of the nation Monday,
while sunny skies prevailed across the southern states. Snow
showers were scattered across the Great Lakes region, the Ohio
Valley and the mid-Atlantic Coast states.
   A weekend snowstorm in northern Maine left Caribou under 21
inches of fresh snow, for a total depth of 30 inches, and high wind
caused widespread drifting.
   The strong winds east of the Rockies helped temperatures warm
into the 50s and lower 60s in Montana on Monday. Brisk southwest
winds warmed readings into the 60s across the central Plains region
with 60s and lower 70s in the southern Plains.
   Mild weather prevailed across the West. The mercury rose to the
50s and lower 60s along the northern Pacific Coast and temperatures
warmed into the 70s and lower 80s in Southern California.
   Monday's high in the nation was 83 degrees at Woodland Hills,
Cal.
   The low was 20 degrees below zero at Watertown, N.Y.
   Other reports at 3 a.m. EST:
   _East: Albany, N.Y. 04 fair; Atlanta 36 fair; Boston 15 fair;
Buffalo 19 cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 41 fair; Chattanooga 41 fair;
Cincinnati 36 fair; Cleveland 20 fair; Detroit 24 foggy; Hatteras
47 windy; Jacksonville 38 fair; Key West 65 fair; Knoxville 37
fair; Macon 33 fair; Miami 56 fair; New York 28 cloudy;
Philadelphia 29 cloudy; Pittsburgh 29 cloudy; Portland, Maine 08
fair; Richmond 30 fair; Tampa 42 fair; Washington, D.C. 33 cloudy.
   _Central: Birmingham 38 fair; Bismarck 35 fair; Chicago 35
cloudy; Denver 52 fair; Des Moines 42 partly cloudy; Fort Worth 44
fair; Indianapolis 33 partly cloudy; Kansas City 43 fair; Little
Rock 42 fair; Louisville 43 partly cloudy; Memphis 42 fair;
Nashville 43 fair; New Orleans 38 fair; North Platte 44 cloudy;
Oklahoma City 47 fair; Omaha 44 partly cloudy; Rapid City 45 fair;
St. Louis 43 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 33 cloudy; Sault Ste. Marie
18 cloudy; San Antonio 45 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 35 fair; Anchorage 27 cloudy; Boise 40
showery; Casper 44 windy; Fairbanks 14 cloudy; Great Falls 52
showery; Honolulu 69 fair; Las Vegas 44 fair; Los Angeles 56 fair;
Medford 53 rain; Pendleton 51 fair; Phoenix 52 fair; Portland, Or.
50 fair; Reno 34 cloudy; Salt Lake City 31 hazy; San Diego 55 fair;
San Francisco 49 fair; Seattle 50 fair; Spokane 42 foggy.
   _International: Calgary 34 partly cloudy; Montreal 01 fair;
Ottawa 05 fair; Regina 30 partly cloudy; Toronto 18 snow.
