<FIRST>r a PM-Addict-Monastery     12-05 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Addict-Monastery,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Gives Drug Addict Two Years in Monastery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEESBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ruled that a longtime heroin
user can spend two years in a Zen Buddhist monastery in New York
rather than the five years in prison he was sentenced to earlier
this year.
   Loudoun County Circuit Judge James H. Chamblin, who issued the
ruling Monday, said Keith Brian Scofield's jail term would be
retained until he completes the two-year program at a monastery in
Sullivan County, N.Y., in the Catskills Mountains.
   Scofield, 30, described himself as a drug addict desperate to
fill a ``spiritual void'' in his life.
   The Sterling, Va., resident was arrested for possession of
heroin in August 1987, convicted in November 1988 and released on
probation. After a June 1989 arrest on a minor charge, Chamblin
gave him the five-year sentence.
   Acting Abbot Junpo Dennis Kelly, who will be legally responsible
for Scofield while he is at the monastery, said ``life here is very
strict,'' with the daily regimen including chants in four languages
beginning at 5 a.m.
   Scofield told The Washington Post he has entered five drug
rehabilitation programs, completed three and feared he would
relapse back ``to the same meaninglessness'' and addiction without
a highly structured program of spiritual therapy. ``This is not
something I'm doing to dodge time,'' he said.
</TEXT>
