<FIRST>r a PM-Eliana-Funeral     12-05 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eliana-Funeral,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young AIDS Victim Laid to Rest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 8-year-old AIDS victim whose family
battled for 2{ years so she could attend school was laid to rest
with her Raggedy Ann doll after a procession took her casket past
the school and courthouse.
   Eliana Martinez, who died last week, was buried Monday in a
funeral full of balloons, songs, praise and memories of the fight
over her education.
   Her adoptive mother, Rosa Martinez, finally won the long court
battle, but the mentally disabled child went to school for only
three weeks this year. She grew too ill to continue.
   ``Eliana taught us to hug and to kiss,'' Mrs. Martinez said.
``She takes a part of me with her. Her legacy is there will be
other children going to school.''
   The funeral procession wound past the Manhattan Exceptional
Center, where Mrs. Martinez released balloons; past the U.S.
Courthouse where she won her suit; and past the Hillsborough County
School Board offices where educators fought Eliana's admission to
class.
   At the gravesite, Eliana's small white casket was opened for her
mother to kiss her goodbye.
   Strands of the colorful glass beads which Eliana liked had been
placed around her neck, and her Raggedy Ann doll laid on her chest.
She was in a white dress with blue ribbons.
   During a 90-minute service at the funeral home chapel, Eliana
was remembered as a frail child who never learned to speak, yet
taught adults the language of love.
   Playing in the background was ``Everybody's Child,'' a song
composed by family friend Linda Castellano.
   Teacher Peggy Kelly told about 125 mourners that ``never have I
seen a person communicate so much with so little words. This child
had no ugliness in her at all ... she was always there for you.''
   Mrs. Martinez adopted Eliana when she was 11 months old after
hearing a radio appeal for a sickly child abandoned in a Puerto
Rico hospital.
   It wasn't until four years later that Mrs. Martinez, her husband
Joe and their son Joey learned Eliana had acquired immune
deficiency syndrome. By the time she was four months old, Eliana
had received 38 transfusions, and doctors believed she received
tainted blood.
   Education officials in Hillsborough County tried to keep Eliana
on homebound instruction, fearing the risk of transmitting AIDS to
other children. Mrs. Martinez sued, saying Eliana needed peer
contact to develop.
   A federal judge said the child could attend classes only if she
sat inside a specially-built glass booth. Mrs. Martinez appealed
that decision and won.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
