<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 0606EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Notebook     12-05 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Notebook,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Day Five: Balloon Vendors, Pink Swimsuits, Destroyed Shack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Philippines, Bjt ^By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rowena Cruz stood in the doorway of
her tiny wooden shack early today and pointed to the bed where a
brother and cousin had been fast asleep just a half hour earlier.
   The bed and covers bore dark stains from the blood of the two
men, who were wounded when a 60mm mortar exploded next to the hut
shortly after dawn.
   The attack apparently came from rebels holed up in nearby
skyskcrapers during the fifth day of their coup against President
Corazon Aquino. The intended target, a battalion of loyalist
marines massing a block from the huts, was unscathed.
   The impoverished neighborhood took the full force of the mortar.
   Blood trailed from the shacks to the Makati Medical Center
across the street, where nine injured civilians were rushed for
treatment and a 6-year-old girl was declared dead on arrival.
   Inside, a young boy lay dazed on one emergency room table, blood
smeared along his legs, while a 4-year-old girl screamed in pain as
doctors disinfected a flesh wound on her back as hospital staff
looked on.
   ``Almost all of them are stable,'' Dr. Phillip Ong said of the
morning's first casualties.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   John Knight, wearing only electric-pink swimming trunks and a
Casio watch, said enough was enough. The rest of this coup would be
spent poolside at the Westin Philippine Plaza.
   ``Four days shut up in a house is too much,'' said Knight, 41,
one of hundreds of foreigners who fled their homes in rebel-held
suburb of Makati today. ``We were running out of food and the wife
and kids were getting psychologically tense.''
   Knight, of London, brought his wife, 10-year-old son and
11-year-old daughter to the Plaza to escape the firefight between
rebel and loyalist troops just blocks from their home. Several
embassies early today phoned their nationals in Makati urging them
to flee.
   Although Knight left his home early enough to book a room, the
U.S., Canadian and Japanese embassies reserved Plaza ballrooms to
shelter the hundreds of foreign residents who arrived after the
hotel filled up.
   The Plaza, overlooking Manila Bay and fully equipped with pool
(including slide), miniature golf and Mongolian barbecue, provided
a distinctly pleasant change of environment for the Makati
residents.
   ``They were firing directly underneath me in the morning,'' said
Harman Schteiden, 34, of Santa Clara, Calif., as he recounted his
decision to leave his home at 6 a.m. Now he was stretched out on a
chaise lounge, a three-day-old USA Today in hand.
   ``I just figured I was out of food, the electricity was out
because of the firing and I had no exercise for two or three days,
Schteiden said. ``I took two shirts, two pants, underwear, a
toothbrush and my shaver, and that's it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Back in Makati, it was quickly apparent that the Philippine
Constabulary fighting the rebels do not dress as a team.
   Some wore regulation boots, others slippers.
   Some wore khaki, others prefer T-shirts.
   Many opted for regulation helmets, but at least one dressed for
battle in a turqouise-and-pink Miami Vice baseball cap.
   One soldier clutched his M-16 in hands covered by black woolen
gloves.
   They all affixed yellow or blue ribbons to their uniforms,
however, so they could distinguish themselves from the rebels.
   Meanwhle, some civilians refused to stop working as loyalist
soldiers took up positions along Makati's streets. As marines
crisscrossed major roads dodging sniper fire just two blocks from
rebel strongholds, vendors strolled by selling cigarettes and
balloons and blithely ignoring roadblock signs saying, ``No Entry,
War Ahead,'' ``War Zone,'' and ``Danger: Men at Fight.''
</TEXT>
