<FIRST>r a PM-JusticeDenied-Arrest     12-05 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Justice Denied-Arrest,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>President of Justice Denied Arrested on Drug Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Justice Denied, a group formed to
release innocent people from prison, was in jail today on drug
charges after an FBI agent recognized his photograph in a
newspaper, officials said.
   Jim Humphreys was charged Monday with 10 counts of possession
with intent to distribute and distribution of heroin from a 1985
indictment, according to FBI spokesman Woody Specht. He was being
held in lieu of $25,000 bond, Specht said.
   The agent saw Humphreys' picture in a Dallas newspaper, from a
ceremony Saturday when Humphreys announced formation of the
organization.
   Among those attending the ceremony were Randall Dale Adams,
whose wrongful conviction for the murder of a police officer was
the subject of the documentary ``The Thin Blue Line.'' Adams was
freed earlier this year after spending 13 years in Texas prisons.
   Humphreys had served as an investigator in the case that led to
freedom for Lenell Geter, an engineer who spent two years in prison
for a robbery he didn't commit.
   Edith Neely Crosby, treasurer of Justice Denied, said she had
not heard about Humphreys' arrest, but felt it would not deter the
goals of the organization.
   ``I'm greatly surprised by it,'' she said. ``It's not going to
interfere with Justice Denied. There are too many people involved
with it and they are too dedicated to it. We will continue on.''
</TEXT>
