<DOCNO> AP891205-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 0621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-St.LouisNewspapers     12-05 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-St. Louis Newspapers,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Everyone's Happy in St. Louis Newspaper Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publishers of St. Louis' two competing
newspapers, including the nation's newest daily, say their
long-anticipated ``newspaper war'' has resulted only in the sale of
more papers.
   The St. Louis Sun, which debuted Sept. 25, has averaged 107,000
readers a day in its first two months, while the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch's circulation has remained steady at 378,000 daily
and 565,000 on Sunday.
   ``We look on it as a competition, which is something different
than a war,'' said Ralph Ingersoll II, the Sun's editor-in-chief
and the chairman and chief executive officer of its parent company,
Ingersoll Publications Co.
   Ingersoll and Nicholas Penniman IV, publisher of the
111-year-old Post-Dispatch and vice president of the Pulitzer
Publishing Co., spoke Monday at the annual meeting of the Missouri
and Kansas Associated Press Publishers and Editors.
   ``I do firmly believe that the Post-Dispatch is a much better
newspaper today than it was a year ago,'' Penniman said.
   The Post-Dispatch's Saturday newspaper has increased its
circulation about 3 percent to 348,000 since the Sun began
appearing with its expanded Saturday paper that costs $1 compared
to 25 cents for the Post-Dispatch.
   Ingersoll said he still expected the Sun to turn a profit by the
end of 1990, but that profits won't be as high as originally
projected because of the large number of home subscribers taking
the Sun. Home subscribers pay less.
   He said he expects the Sun's circulation by the end of 1990 to
be about 125,000.
   David Lipman, managing editor of the Post-Dispatch, said the new
competition has accelerated changes at the newspaper and given it a
jolt of adrenalin.
   ``The Post-Dispatch feels 10 years younger. And we're going to
continue feeling young and being useful and still be a lot of
fun,'' he said.
   Before the debut of the Sun, the Post-Dispatch had been without
competition since the St. Louis Globe-Democrat folded in October
1986.
</TEXT>
