<FIRST>r a PM-FoolsCrowFuneral     12-05 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fools Crow Funeral,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sioux Indian Leader Buried Monday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAFKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KYLE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several hundred mourners paid final respects
to Chief Frank Fools Crow in a ceremony that was done in the
traditional Sioux culture with medicine men and with Christian
services by Episcopalian ministers.
   An estimated 700 people attended the nearly five-hour observance
Monday for the Oglala Sioux chief and medicine man believed to be
99 years old.
   The funeral, held in the Little Wound School gymnasium, featured
many aspects of Indian culture, including a full-sized tepee, war
bonnets and colorful quilts. A riderless horse, bearing a blanket
and war bonnet that signified Fools Crow's death, led the wooden
wagon to the graveyard. About 60 horses and riders and a string of
cars two miles long were in tow.
   ``When a warrior dies, they take their horse so the journey into
the spirit world is a good one,'' said Severt Young Bear of
Porcupine.
   Family members rode in a limousine owned by Dennis Banks, a
co-founder of the once-militant American Indian Movement. Banks and
AIM co-founder Russell Means traveled to Kyle to pay last respects
to Fools Crow.
   ``A lot of young people have come back to the traditional ways
because of him,'' Banks said.
   Banks said few people know it was Fools Crow who decided that
Wounded Knee should be the site of a 1973 armed confrontation
between about 300 AIM supporters and 300 federal lawmen.
   ``He knew something was going to happen, so he said we should go
back to Wounded Knee,'' Banks said.
   Two Indians were killed in the 71-day takeover and two law
officers were wounded.
   Banks said representatives of 80 to 90 Indian tribes were at the
funeral.
   ``I've never seen a funeral the size of this,'' he said.
   Fools Crow was a teacher who helped preserve the Indian way of
life, said Francis Whitebird, state Indian affairs coordinator.
   ``He had a tremendous mental capacity. He saw the world. He
understood things,'' Whitebird said.
   Joe Cash, director of the Institute of Indian Studies at the
University of South Dakota, said Fools Crow will be remembered more
as a medicine man than as a chief. He said those who took part in
the 1973 Wounded Knee uprising used Fools Crow as an example of how
Indians should live.
   ``He became sort of a religious symbol of the old way of doing
things,'' Cash said.
   Although births of many Indians were not recorded when South
Dakota first joined the union, the widely respected spiritual
leader was believed to be 99 years old. He died Nov. 27.
   Born on the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation, one of the most
economically depressed areas of the country, Fools Crow quit school
in the third grade to help his family earn a living.
   He later traveled throughout the United States with the Buffalo
Bill Cody Wild West Show.
   Fools Crow lived with grandchildren near Kyle after the death of
his second wife, Kate, last year. He had four children with his
first wife, Fannie Afraid Of Hawk, who died in 1954.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
