<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 0644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AutoRecall     12-05 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Recall,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lexus LS400 Cars Recalled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Corp. has recalled every Lexus LS400
luxury automobile sold in the United States so far because of a
sticky cruise control mechanism and defective stoplight cover.
   The recall announced Monday is the first for Lexus, which went
on sale in early September. November sales figures were due out
later today, but company officials estimated that about 8,000 cars
would be affected by the recall.
   The Lexus division of Toyota also makes and markets the ES250
automobile, which is not subject to the recall.
   ``We haven't had any accidents or injuries,'' Lexus Vice
President Dave Illingworth said. He said the two problems had
brought one customer complaint each.
   In addition to the cruise control and stoplamp problems, Lexus
mechanics also will be sure that a wiring connector between the
alternator and the battery is seated properly. If not clicked into
place, battery power could be drained, Lexus spokesman Kurt Von
Zumwalt said.
   ``It's hard in the short term, but in the long term it will help
our image,'' Von Zumwalt said in a telephone interview from his
office in California.
   The company said it would replace a cruise control actuator,
which controls the throttle.
   He also said the plastic covering on the center-mounted
stoplight would be replaced because letting the light burn too long
could melt the covering.
   Letters were to be sent today to owners of the LS400, which
sells for $35,000, telling them to take their cars to the nearest
Lexus dealership.
   ``We believe that we will have everything handled within two to
three weeks,'' Illingworth said.
</TEXT>
