<SECOND>PM-Election Rdp,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Election Issues: Taxes in North Dakota; Abortion, Housing in California</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to CORRECT category code.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Taxes, gambling and sex education are among the issues North
Dakotans vote on today, while abortion and housing, respectively,
are central to two local California elections.
   North Dakota Secretary of State Jim Kusler predicted 150,000
voters would turn out for today's special election, which includes
seven referendums _ the most on the state's ballot since 1919.
   Gov. George Sinner has conducted an extensive statewide campaign
to push for increases in the state's taxes on sales, income and
motor fuels.
   In addition to the three tax referendums, voters are being asked
to approve mandatory sex education in public schools, a mandatory
seat-belt law, a retirement program for legislators and
legalization of video gambling machines. The ballot also includes a
proposed constitutional amendment to reorganize the executive
branch of state government.
   In California's San Diego County, a state Senate election has
drawn national headlines because one of the candidates, a Roman
Catholic, is the country's first public official to be denied
Communion because of her advocacy of abortion rights.
   Assemblywoman Lucy Killea, a Democrat and the underdog in a
heavily Republican district, has said she will abide by the ban
imposed by Bishop Leo T. Maher, and will not change her stance.
   Her opponent, first-year Assemblywoman Carol Bentley, a
Republican and abortion opponent, has tried to stay away from the
controversy.
   The special election is being held to fill a vacancy created
when the incumbent was made a municipal judge.
   In northern California, Watsonville is holding a city council
election that originally was scheduled for Nov. 7 but was postponed
after the Oct. 17 earthquake, which destroyed more than 300 homes
in the town 95 miles south of San Francisco.
   The election will mark the first time Watsonville has elected
city council members by district. A court ordered the city to end
its tradition of at-large elections because they discriminated
against Hispanic residents, who are about half of the town's
population of 30,000.
   Sixteen candidates, five of them Hispanic, are vying for seven
seats on the new council. Housing and development, which were big
issues before the quake, have loomed even larger in the aftermath
of the disaster.
</TEXT>
