<FIRST>u a PM-Marcos-Murders 2ndLd-Writethru a0520 12-05 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos-Murders, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0520,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seattle Trial Watches Philippines Coup Attempt Anxiously</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `As a...' to restore first name of Ms. Domingo.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attempted military coup in the Philippines has
given some anxious moments to plaintiffs who are depending on a key
witness to leave that country and testify in federal court.
   The wrongful-death lawsuit accuses former Philippines President
Ferdinand Marcos, his widow, Imelda, and others of arranging the
June 1981 murders of two Seattle union activists because of their
anti-Marcos activities.
   One key witness is Bonifacio Gillego, a one-time member of
Marcos' intelligence network who later rebelled against Marcos and
now is a House member under the government of President Corazon
Aquino.
   Gillego is expected to ``draw a lot of the threads together''
from previous testimony about Marcos intelligence agents operating
in the United States, said Sharon Maeda, spokeswoman for the
Committee for Justice for Domingo and Viernes.
   Silme Domingo and Gene Viernes were activist reformers in the
Alaska Cannery Workers Union. They were shot in union offices in
Seattle on June 1, 1981.
   As a legislator, Gillego was required to obtain special
permission to leave the Philippines during the coup emergency, said
Domingo's sister, Cindy Domingo. At last report he had obtained
that permission, but still faced the task of trying to get a flight
out of the country to appear here, probably next week.
   At least 70 people have been killed and more than 500 wounded
since mutineers seized several military installations and bombed
the presidential palace in Manila on Friday, according to the Red
Cross.
   The chances of Gillego being able to attend ``look very good,''
Ms. Domingo said Monday. Less certain was the status of Randolph
David, a Philippines university professor who was scheduled to
testify about Marcos' martial-law regime.
   If David is unable to leave the Philippines, he would likely
give a deposition by telephone, Ms. Domingo said.
   Three men have been convicted of murdering the two men,
allegedly in an internal union dispute. But plaintiffs claim
Marcos' government marked the men for death because of their
anti-Marcos activities, including support for anti-Marcos trade
unionists in the Philippines.
   The suit, filed in September 1982, seeks $30 million on behalf
of the men's families. In addition to the Marcoses, defendants
include the men convicted of the murders; the Philippines
government; Dr. Leonilo Malabed of San Francisco, a Marcos friend
who ran the Mabuhay Corp.; and Constantine Baruso, a former union
president whose gun was used in the killings. Baruso was never
charged in the killings.
   It was Gillego, in particular, who drew the plaintiffs'
attention to the most important document in the case: a supposed
account sheet for the Mabuhay Corp., a San Francisco company that
plaintiffs claim was used to funnel money from the Philippines to
agents in this country.
   That account sheet includes a $15,000 entry that plaintiffs
claim was money used to pay for the murders.
</TEXT>
