<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon-Raid 2ndLd-Writethru   12-05 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Raid, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0521,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Warplanes Strike Abu Nidal Base</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with number of casualties, details;
pickup 9th graf pvs, `Smoke billowed...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes today attacked a
Palestinian guerrilla base near this southern port city, wounding
seven people, most of them Palestinian civilians, police said.
   Four fighters struck the base of terrorist mastermind Abu
Nidal's Fatah Revolutionary Council in the Majdalioun Valley, east
of Sidon, a police spokesman said.
   However, an Israeli army announcement in Jerusalem said
warplanes struck a headquarters and a base of the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, headed by former
Syrian army Capt. Ahmed Jibril.
   There was no immediate explanation for the conflicting reports.
   The Lebanese police spokesman said most of the casualties were
Palestinian civilians seeking medical treatment at a Palestinian
guerrilla-run clinic when the Israeli warplanes struck.
   The Israeli army said all aircraft returned safely from the noon
raid.
   The police spokesman, who cannot be named in line with
regulations, said the jets fired eight rockets at the Abu Nidal
base and flew west over the Mediterranean.
   ``It was a swift attack. It only lasted a few minutes,'' the
spokesman said. Guerrilla defenders ``hardly managed to open fire
from anti-aircraft guns. No hits were observed,'' he added.
   He said Abu-Nidal's guerrillas immediately blocked all
approaches to the valley as their jeeps and ambulances evacuated
casualties to hospitals in Sidon.
   Smoke billowed from the valley as the guerrillas fired rifles in
the air to make way for their ambulances.
   Two Swiss Red Cross workers kidnapped in Sidon Oct. 6 are
believed held in the valley.
   The attack was Israel's 17th air raid in Lebanon this year.
   By police count, 18 people were killed and 109 wounded in the 16
previous attacks. The latest was Nov. 25 against the Popular Front
for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command in southeastern
Lebanon.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri al-Banna, broke away from
Yasser Arafat's mainstream Fatah group in the early 1970s and
formed his own group.
   Abu Nidal is reported ill or under house arrest at his
headquarters in Libya.
</TEXT>
