<HEAD>French Association Give Lost Canadian Pilot Honorable Burial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Other witnesses ...' to change jet to plane.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIRE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian pilot shot down in 1944 was
buried today in a military cemetery surrounded by family, friends
and members of a French association searching for Allied soldiers
lost during the Battle of Normandy.
   A.E. Miron was a 25-year-old fighter pilot on Aug. 17, 1944, the
day his ``Typhoon'' was hit by a German shell.
   ``I was flying in formation with Miron when I saw his plane come
from behind and crash to earth,'' recalled John Thompson, a member
of the squadron who was interviewed by the French news agency
Agence France-Presse.
   Other witnesses told the association, Wings of Victory, that the
plane plunged into a haystack that camouflaged Nazi anti-aircraft
artillery. The information helped the group locate the remains of
Miron, who had been listed as missing, in a Normany field on Sept.
2.
   Miron was buried with 799 of his comrades in the small British
military cemetery of Saint-Charles-de-Percy, AFP reported.
   Jacques Brehin, president of the association, said seven lost
aircraft have been found since his group began looking in 1984. He
said 15 pilots are still listed as missing from the 151 who were
shot down during the prolonged battle to liberate France.
   No information was immediately available on Miron's home town.
