<FIRST>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     12-05 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preschool Molest,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Ponders Whether To Cancel Vacation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a month of deliberations, the jury in
the McMartin preschool molestation trial is discussing a new
subject _ whether or not to interrupt deliberations for a Christmas
vacation.
   The jurors were confronted with the option Monday after Superior
Court Judge William Pounders yielded to their concerns and decided
not to announce partial verdicts before the scheduled Christmas
break on Dec. 15.
   He urged jurors to reconsider whether they want to take the two
weeks off or continue deliberating.
   ``Our concern is with you,'' he said. ``We have to keep you
together, healthy and hopefully happy and not so angry at each
other that we lose one of you.''
   The jurors retired to their deliberation room but had not
announced their decision by day's end.
   Three jurors had told the judge earlier they were worried about
community pressure on them if partial verdicts were publicized
before the entire 65 counts were resolved.
   The jurors are considering 65 separate charges against Raymond
Buckey, 31, and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, 62, who are
accused of molesting children at their family owned preschool in
Manhattan Beach.
   The 2{-year-old trial is the longest and costliest criminal
proceeding in Los Angeles and U.S. history, and the judge has said
he's determined to get verdicts. Six original alternates were used
up as illness and job problems caused them to drop out. All
verdicts must be unanimous, and loss of one juror now could cause a
mistrial.
   In an unusual plan, Pounders asked the jury to deliver sealed
verdicts as they decided individual counts. But since no verdict is
final until it is announced in court and affirmed by all jurors, he
had planned to announce a partial verdict before the vacation.
   He intended the vacation to give jurors respite from stress of
deliberations, which could take months. But on Monday it turned out
that at least seven jurors planned to return to their jobs during
the break rather than take vacations.
   Pounders then suggested they might want to cancel the vacation.
However, at least one juror has purchased plane tickets for an out
of state trip and would lose money if it was canceled, he said.
</TEXT>
