<FILEID>AP-PX-12-05-89 1137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Unions     12-05 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Unions,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Makes it Easier for Workers to Sue Unions in Ohio Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today made it easier for
workers to sue their unions over alleged failures to provide fair
representation.
   The court unanimously reinstated a federal lawsuit a Toledo,
Ohio, area sheet metal worker filed against his union five years
ago.
   Lynn L. Breininger's suit contends that Local 6 of the Sheet
Metal Workers International Association discriminated against him
in referring work out of its hiring hall.
   Lower courts had thrown out the suit, ruling that Breininger was
alleging an unfair labor practice and that the National Labor
Relations Board has exclusive jurisdiction over such claims.
   Those courts were wrong, the justices said today.
   ``That a breach of duty of fair representation might also be an
unfair labor practice is not enough to deprive a federal court of
jurisdiction over the fair representation claim,'' Justice William
J. Brennan wrote.
   He added: ``Federal courts have jurisdiction to hear
fair-representation suits whether or not they are accompanied by
claims against employers.''
   Local 6 represents sheet metal workers who work for various
employers in the Toledo area. The union has collective bargaining
agreements with two associations of employers.
   The union operates a job-referral system out of a union hiring
hall.
   Breininger, a longtime union member, alleges that the union
refused to honor employers' specific requests for his services and
unjustifiably passed him over in making referrals.
   His suit also contended that Local 6 had violated the federal
Labor-Management Reporting and Disclosure Act of 1959 by, in
effect, disciplining him because he had politically opposed some
union leaders.
   Today's decision was not a total defeat for Local 6. The
justices, by a 7-2 vote, said lower courts were right in ruling
that the union's alleged failure to refer Breininger for jobs
through its hiring hall is not, even if true, a violation of the
1959 law.
   That still left Breininger free to pursue his
fair-representation claim in federal court.
   Justices John Paul Stevens and Antonin Scalia dissented from
that part of the court's decision. They said Breininger should be
allowed to sue over the alleged violation of the 1959 law in
addition to the alleged failure of fair representation.
   The case is Breininger vs. Sheet Metal Workers, 88-124.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
