<FIRST>r a PM-NuclearSecurity-Lab     12-05 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Security-Lab,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawrence Livermore Lab Denies Report of Security Lapses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIVERMORE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at the Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory denied a congressional report that said there
were serious security lapses involving large amounts of plutonium.
   ``At no time has plutonium been unprotected,'' said L. Lynn
Cleland, acting manager of the weapons lab's safeguards and
security. Cleland, at a news conference Monday, called Lawrence
Livermore's plutonium building ``one of our most highly secured
facilities.''
   According to a report released Sunday, the federal weapons lab
35 miles east of San Francisco had left the radioactive material _
enough for a nuclear weapon _ unattended.
   The report included transcripts of testimony by Department of
Energy officials at a hearing last July before the House Energy and
Commerce subcommitee on oversight and investigations. The panel is
investigating the Department of Energy's weapons facilities.
   According to the transcript of the testimony, Edward J.
McCallum, the DOE's top security evaluator, testified that
Livermore lab security ``has not been effective.''
   Amounts of plutonium and other nuclear weapons materials were
``left unattended in unalarmed rooms during off-shift hours,''
McCallum said. Previous security measures were inadequate to
protect the material from sabotage or theft, but the lab has since
corrected the problem, he said.
   Cleland, while insisting no plutonium was unprotected and that
none of it was missing, said the lab agreed with a DOE
recommendation to improve security.
   ``There were deficiencies, but we did not feel they were very
serious, but they were serious enough that they needed to be
addressed and we addressed them,'' he said.
   Livermore ranked lowest of all 26 nuclear weapons facilities in
the nation for safeguarding nuclear weapons materials, according to
the testimony. Lab officials said they didn't know how the DOE
arrived at that ranking.
</TEXT>
