<FIRST>u a PM-RiotTrial 3rdLd-Writethru a0555 12-05 0811</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riot Trial, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0555,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>Closing Arguments Begin in Miami Officer's Manslaughter Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with defense attorney's closing
arguments. Picks up 3rd graf, `Horn said ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for a policeman who shot a black
motorcyclist pleaded with jurors today to consider only the facts
in the officer's manslaughter trial, not the impact their verdict
might have on race relations.
   The city has girded itself against a repeat of the racial
violence that raged for three days after Colombian-born officer
William Lozano, 31, shot and killed Clement Lloyd on Jan. 16 as the
motorcyclist sped away from a patrol car. Lloyd's passenger, Allan
Blanchard, died of injuries suffered in the motorcycle crash.
   ``This case has nothing to do with racial prejudice,'' said
defense attorney Roy Black, giving his closing argument in a low,
measured tone. ``Your verdict has meaning only in its truth to the
case and its effects on a police officer. No one here is trying to
cause any further problems, all we are seeking is the truth in this
case.''
   Earlier, the prosecution argued that Lozano could have avoided a
confrontation before the shooting. It ``was not a life-or-death
situation'' for Lozano, prosecutor Don Horn told jurors. ``It was
not a split-second decision.''
   Horn said all of the prosecution witnesses had heard the
motorcycle approaching from at least a block away, while Lozano
claimed he never noticed it until it was almost upon him.
   ``He stepped out there, he decided he was going to shoot, and he
shot,'' Horn said. ``All he had to do was step behind the police
car.''
   Lozano is charged with two counts of manslaughter and faces a
maximum of 30 years in jail on each count.
   Jurors would have to decide if Lozano acted as a ``reasonably
cautious and prudent police officer,'' Horn said.
   Horn then reviewed arguments on both sides with the intent of
showing that Lozano was not threatened by the motorcyclist and did
not have to shoot him in self-defense.
   Attorneys predicted the case could be in the hands of the jurors
by the end of the day.
   On two previous occasions in this decade, riots broke out when
white officers were acquitted in the slayings of blacks.
   Prosecutors say Lloyd fired unnecessarily as the motorcycle
passed him at a safe distance. The defense argues that Lozano fired
only at the last second to protect his life as the motorcycle bore
down on him in the wrong lane.
   Jurors heard from almost 60 witnesses after testimony began Nov.
15. The trial opened Oct. 23, but it took more than three weeks to
seat a jury of two blacks, one Hispanic and three non-Hispanic
whites.
   Following the close of testimony Monday, the judge and lawyers
for both sides hashed out instructions to be given to the jury
before deliberations.
   The prosecution won efforts to exclude much of Florida's
``fleeing felon'' law from the instructions. The law allows police
to fire on suspected criminals, but Dade Circuit Judge Joseph
Farina disallowed it on grounds that Lozano never testified he was
trying to make an arrest at the time of the shooting.
   The defense, won an instruction that if Lloyd was committing
aggravated assault _ which can include causing a ``well-founded
fear'' of death or injury _ Lozano could be found innocent for
shooting him.
   Defense attorneys rested their case earlier Monday after rolling
a Kawasaki Ninja motorcycle similar to Lloyd's into the courtroom.
   Attorney Mark Seiden had an expert testify about the cycle's
measurements to show the bullet could have entered Lloyd's head at
an angle _ as the autopsy showed _ even if the bike was headed
directly at the officer.
   The defense also put officer Felix Martinez on the stand to
testify about a 1988 incident in which Lozano allegedly forced a
man's head into the officer's chest during an argument. The
prosecution claims the incident shows Lozano had a hot temper when
his authority was challenged, but the defense claims the story was
made up.
   The motorcycle shooting occurred on Martin Luther King's
birthday as Miami began a week of celebration leading up to the
Super Bowl. Lozano and his partner Dawn Campbell were stopped on a
street in a black neighborhood.
   Another squad car was chasing down Lloyd's motorcycle, which
raced past the street where Lozano stood. The officer fired one
shot, killing Lloyd instantly and sending the motorcycle crashing
into a car.
   Within an hour after the shooting, an angry crowd gathered at
the scene and began pelting officers with rocks and bottles.
   The violence spread. By the time it ended three days later, one
looter had been shot to death, 11 people were wounded by gunfire
and 13 buildings were burned down in the Overtown and Liberty City
neighborhoods.
</TEXT>
