<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Amaldi     12-05 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Amaldi,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Nuclear Physicist Dead at 81</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edoardo Amaldi, considered one of the fathers of
Italian physics and a pioneer in nuclear research, died Tuesday at
the age of 81.
   Amaldi fell ill at the Lincei Academy, a Rome research institute
of which he was president, and died a short while later at a nearby
hospital, officials said. The exact cause of death was not
announced.
   Born in 1908 in Carpaneto Fiorentino in the Emilia-Romagna
region of northern Italy, Amaldi studied under physicist Enrico
Fermi, winner of the Nobel Prize in 1938 for his research on
nuclear fission.
   Amaldi served for 41 years as a physics professor at the
University of Rome.
   He was a driving force in the creation of the Geneva-based
European Council for Nuclear Research, now called the European
Laboratory for Particle Physics. He was secretary general of the
organization from 1952-54.
   From 1958-59, Amaldi was president of the scientific and
technical committee of the European Atomic Energy Community.
   Funeral services were scheduled for Thursday.
</TEXT>
