<DOCNO> AP891205-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-05-89 1225EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Computer     12-05 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Computer,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Computer Virus Hits Osaka University</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A virus from abroad has entered a computer system
at Osaka University but caused no major disturbance, an official
said Tuesday.
   The virus was detected Oct. 19 in one of four computers linked
to a high energy physics network that also includes the United
States and Europe, said Shojiro Sugimoto, an official at the school
in western Japan. The virus was removed immediately and there was
no major damage to computers, he said.
   A virus, apparently from abroad, also was detected in computers
at Tokyo University's Atomic Nucleus Research Institute and Tokyo
Metropolitan University, but there were no reports of major damage,
the Japan Broadcasting Corp. reported Tuesday.
   Computer viruses, created by unknown programmers, are pieces of
software that reproduce themselves and spread from one machine to
another through infected floppy disks, office networks or telephone
lines. They erode a computer's processing power and storage space,
or destroy information.
   A virus disrupted computers at the University of Tokyo's
seismological and ocean research institutes in October. That virus
infected only personal computers being used by researchers, and not
major computer systems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891205-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-05-89 1226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Elwyn-Jones     12-05 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Elwyn-Jones,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuremberg War Crimes Prosecutor Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lord Elwyn-Jones, a prosecutor at the Nuremberg
war crimes trials and Britain's chief legal officer under the last
Labor Party government, has died of cancer at the age of 80.
   He died at his home in Brighton on Monday night, said his son,
Dan.
   Elwyn-Jones remained active in politics until his death, and
attended the ceremonial opening of Parliament last month. He had
been scheduled to be in the House of Lords on Monday to give
Labor's views on whether the government should permit the
prosecution of alleged Nazi war criminals living in Britain.
   ``The memories of Nuremberg are still vivid in my memory,'' he
said in July. ``The millions deliberately put to death _ that
cannot be passed over as a mere aberration which should be
forgotten in the mere tide of history.''
   He was born Frederick Elwyn-Jones in Wales in 1909, the son of a
frequently unemployed steelworker. He was educated at the
University of Wales and then Cambridge University, where he was
president of the Cambridge Union, the debating society. He became a
lawyer in 1935.
   Elwyn-Jones came to national prominence as a member of the
British War Crimes Executive at Nuremberg in 1945 where he was a
prosecutor at the Nazi trials.
   He was elected to the House of Commons in 1945, and was Attorney
General in Prime Minister Harold Wilson's government from 1964-70
and Lord High Chancellor, the country's top law officer, from
1974-79. He received a peerage and moved to the unelected House of
Lords in 1974.
   Elwyn-Jones was the senior counsel for the tribunal of inquiry
into the 1966 collapse of a coal slag heap in the Welsh village of
Aberfan that killed 116 children and 28 adults.
   He was a government adviser during the 1966 crisis brought on by
Rhodesia's unilateral declaration of independence, and attended
unsuccessful talks with Wilson and Rhodesian Prime Minister Ian
Smith aboard the Royal Navy cruiser HMS Tiger off Gibraltar.
   In 1984, he presided at a mock televised trial that found King
Richard III innocent of the murder of The Little Princes, the two
teen-age nephews he put in the Tower of London because they stood
between him and the throne.
   Elwyn-Jones is survived by his wife, three children and nine
grandchildren.
   A private funeral is planned, with a memorial service to be held
later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891205-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-05-89 1227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Niger     12-05 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Niger,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Niger to Hold First Presidential Election Since Independence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NIAMEY, Niger (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in this West African country go to
the polls Sunday in presidential and legislative elections that are
the first since independence from France in 1960.
   About 3 million voters are expected at the polls to elect 93
deputies to parliament, as well as whether to keep President Ali
Saibou in office. Saibou faces no opposition.
   In 1987, voters approved a national charter that served as the
basis for a constitution that was approved Sept. 24 in this
landlocked nation of about 7 million people in the Sahara north of
Nigeria and south of Libya.
   Under the new constitution, Niger's president serves a
seven-year term.
   The new document is the first since the previous constitution
was suspended in 1974 by Gen. Seyni Kountche who took power in a
military coup during a devastating drought. After Kountche's death
in 1987, Saibou, the former head of Niger's military, was elected
leader by the ruling Supreme Military Council.
   Saibou freed about 100 people imprisoned for coup plots against
Kountche.
   In 1988, Saibou announced the creation of a political party, the
National Movement for a Society of Development. It remains the sole
party and its leader becomes the only candidate for the presidency.
   Saibou, 49, has pledged to put Niger on the path of food
self-sufficiency.
</TEXT>
