<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     12-05 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sudanese Peace Talks Collapse Over Islamic Law Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peace talks between rebels and the
Sudanese government collapsed Tuesday in disagreement over the
country's Islamic legal code and other issues that have kept them
at war for nearly seven years.
   ``In my opinion, neither side came to Nairobi prepared to take
the difficult steps necessary for peace,'' said former President
Jimmy Carter, who acted as an unofficial mediator in the five days
of negotiations.
   ``Both sides, at the end, seemed ready to emphasize their
differences, postpone further action and let the war continue,''
Carter said. ``There is no telling how many hundreds of thousands
of people will die because these two sides have failed to reach an
agreement.''
   Both Carter and Lam Akol, the chief negotiator for the Sudan
People's Liberation Army, said the talks broke down mainly over the
government's failure to address the question of Sudan's Sharia law,
a harsh Islamic legal code.
   The government's chief spokesman, Abdel Samie Omer Ahmed,
disagreed. He said the talks had not broken down but were merely
postponed to give his delegation a chance to confer with the
government.
   No date was given for further negotiations.
   Carter said he proposed the Sudanese government set aside the
Sharia law from the beginning of a cease-fire until the convening
of a constitutional conference to write a new, basic framework of
law for the African nation.
   ``If the government would do that, and only that, I believe
peace would come,'' Carter said. ``I'm not asking them to cancel
it, to abrogate it. I'm just asking them to set it aside for a few
months.''
   He said the rebels had agreed to abide by Sharia law if it were
established as part of the legal code by a broad-based
constitutional convention.
   The chief rebel negotiator said the two sides also had
``fundamental divergences'' on the state of emergency in effect in
Sudan since 1983 and the country's military pacts with Egypt and
Libya.
   But Akol made it clear the rebels view the Islamic law, which
imposes such penalties as cutting off a hand for petty theft, as
the chief stumbling block.
   ``They have to move on Sharia law,'' he said.
   The rebels took up arms in 1983 to press the Moslem-dominated
government for greater political autonomy and larger economic
benefits for the largely Christian southern half of Sudan.
   The war has brought widespread famine to the south. The United
Nations estimated that 250,000 people died in the region in 1988.
</TEXT>
