<FIRST>r w AM-FarmScene 1stLd-Writethru a0584 12-05 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0584,0731</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leahy Says Groundwater Problem Will Head Farm Bill Hearings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Fixes typos and dropped reference to commitee chairman in 1st
item; Picks up 2nd item</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Agriculture
Committee says he will begin hearings on the 1990 farm bill in
January with a session on groundwater problems and he wants the
Environmental Protection Agency to have proposals in hand.
   ``I want them to have specific recommendations,'' Sen. Patrick
Leahy, D-Vt., said Monday after meeting with EPA administrator
William Reilly.
   Leahy said he intended to move the farm bill quickly and wants
it to contain groundwater provisions when it passes the Senate.
   ``I want answers. I don't want to say we're studying it,'' he
said.
   Leahy has been critical of EPA's performance in protecting
groundwater, which is the source of drinking water for many
Americans who use wells.
   ``I am particularly concerned about the well-documented
contamination from nitrates and pesticides,'' Leahy said. ``It is
time for the administration to get off the dime to solve this
pressing problem.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Family Farm Coalition has a
proposal for the 1990 farm bill it says would strengthen family
farms while eliminating the need for deficiency payment subsidies.
   At a news conference Monday, members of the coalition presented
a plan that also would encourage sustainable agriculture, or what
is commonly called organic farming.
   ``For grain handlers and shippers, and for food processors, the
1985 farm bill has ensured record profits,'' said the coalition's
statement. ``For over 400,000 farm and ranch families who left the
land between 1985 and 1988 and their rural communities, that farm
program has been a disaster.''
   The coalition says their model farm bill would:
   _Allow farmers to earn their income from the marketplace by
raising price support levels to cover the cost of production.
   _Establish a farmer commodity reserve that would ensure against
natural disaster and cushion the economic risk of changing from
chemical to sustainable methods.
   _Ensure through production management and a commodity reserve a
stable supply of grain for domestic, foreign trade and food
assistance programs.
   ``There is a growing concern among farmers, consumers and in
Congress that farm commodities be grown with few chemicals,'' said
the coalition's statement.
   The group's proposal would give farmers a two- to five-year
economic cushion while switching from herbicides and pesticides to
sustainable methods through access to reserve crops.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Resources Inventory shows that
sheet and rill erosion on cropland decreased by a half-ton per acre
nationwide between 1982 and 1987, dropping from 4.3 tons to 3.8
tons per acre a year.
   However, wind erosion on cropland increased 0.1 ton per acre to
3.3 tons per acre a year, said the report from the Agriculture
Department's soil conservation service that was issued Monday.
   According to the data, sheet and rill erosion nationwide totals
1.6 billion tons per year and wind erosion 1.4 billion tons
annually.
   The survey ``reveals impressive gains for soil conservation,''
said the Center for Resource Economics, a Washington-based
non-profit environmental research and publishing organization.
   But the research also shows that soil erosion is still a serious
problem, it said in a statement.
   ``From everything we know about land use in the mid-1970s,
erosion conditions worsened with the onset of the export boom,''
said Ken Cook, vice president of the center.
   He said analysis of the survey data may show that the
improvement in erosion control is due substantially to massive
idling of cropland under government programs between 1984 and 1987.
   The Agriculture Department said the report does not reflect the
work under way on about 140 million acres of highly erodible land
as part of the conservation provisions of the 1985 farm law.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty Polish agriculturalists will be coming
to the United States next year to learn about American farming and
agriculture trade methods under a fellowship program for foreign
agriculture officials.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter said Monday that 39 Polish
farm officials participated last April, the largest contingent
among the 16 foreign countries involved.
   He said $90,000 had been set aside through the Cochran Middle
Income Country Fellowship Program to aid Polish participants.
</TEXT>
