<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Armenia     12-05 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Armenia,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenians Surround Legislators, Call Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armenians trapped their lawmakers in their
chambers for hours today and then went on strike to demand stronger
action against Moscow's bid to end a territorial dispute, an
activist said.
   Thousands of people surrounded the Supreme Soviet chambers in
Yerevan, the Armenian capital, Monday night and refused to let the
lawmakers out until 5 a.m., Karen Shakhbazyan said.
   When only 49 of 315 legislators showed up five hours later for
the morning legislative session, Yerevan factory workers went on
strike, he said by telephone from the city.
   The lawmakers spent Monday debating a proposal to drop the words
``Soviet Socialist'' from Armenia's official name and call it
simply the ``Armenian Republic.''
   The legislators did not decide that issue, or a call for them to
boycott a session of the national Congress of People's Deputies
when it meets in Moscow Dec. 12.
   ``The people are demanding that they decide the issue,''
Shakhbazyan said.
   Many Armenians want the lawmakers to boycott the national
legislative session in defiance of Moscow's position over the
disputed Nagorno-Karabakh region.
   Last week, the Armenian legislature declared the republic would
annex the enclave, which is predominantly Armenian and Christian
but part of neighboring Azerbaijan, which is mostly Moslem.
   Nagorno-Karabakh is called an autonomous region but it is
supposed to obey the Azerbaijan government.
   Dozens of people have been killed in the past 18 months in
violence stemming from the territorial dispute.
   Moscow is unlikely to recognize the Armenian annexation.
   The federal Supreme Soviet put Nagorno-Karabakh under the direct
rule of Moscow last year but did away with that arrangement on Nov.
28.
   It directed Azerbaijan to work with local officials to solve
mounting social, economic and political problems in the enclave.
Both Armenians and Azerbaijanis have said they are dissatisfied
with that decision.
</TEXT>
