<HEAD>IBM to Cut 10,000 Jobs, Take $2.3 Billion Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with chairman not expecting closings,
later stock price; picking up 10th graf, `IBM has....' A version moved
on financial wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. announced
today it would cut 10,000 U.S. jobs without layoffs as it copes
with slow growth in the U.S. market.
   The world's largest computer company said it would set aside
$2.3 billion from its pre-tax earnings for the fourth-quarter to
cover costs of employee buyouts and restructuring. IBM said it
would reduce its staff by limiting hiring and offering incentives
to employees to quit or retire early.
   The company did not announce any closings of facilities and John
Akers, the chairman and chief executive, said he did not expect any.
   IBM also announced a program to buy back up to $4 billion of its
own stock, which has lost more than a third of its value since its
1987 peak.
   With the company cost-cutting to improve profitability, IBM's
stock rose $2 a share to $101.25 at midday today on the New York
Stock Exchange after a $2.12{ a share rise on Monday, when
speculation intensified that the company planned to cut jobs.
   The stock's peak price was $175.87{ in August 1987.
   IBM expanded dramatically in the early 1980s but has been
cutting back since 1985, when it became apparent that the
industry's rapid 15 percent annual growth was slowing.
   IBM said its growth overseas was strong, but the U.S. business
still was growing more slowly than desired.
   ``The actions we are describing today underscore our ongoing
resolve to make IBM the most competitive information processing
business in an industry that continues to grow,'' Akers said in a
statement.
   IBM has a 40-year tradition of no layoffs. In a meeting today
with securities analysts, Akers said the company intended to keep
that tradition because it helped the company maintain a
high-quality, flexible and dedicated workforce.
   He added, ``It's impossible to guarantee for all time full
employment under any and all circumstances.''
   The company said its $4 billion stock buyback, in combination
with a $1 billion buyback authorized in October, if completed would
bring total repurchases since mid-1986 to more than $10.5 billion.
That amounts to about 15 percent of the shares outstanding at that
time _ possibly the biggest repurchase program ever undertaken.
   The job cuts are intended to reduce the company's U.S. workforce
to 206,000 by the end of 1990, a reduction of more than 37,000 from
1985 levels.
   The $2.3 billion pre-tax charge against fourth-quarter earnings
breaks down as follows:
   _$500 million for separation payments to people leaving the
company.
   _$500 million for accounting changes to speed up the way IBM
logs its payment for software and technology investments.
   _$1.3 billion for restructuring, including consolidations,
capacity reductions and cuts in the valuation of special
investments such as share ownership in other companies.
</TEXT>
