<FIRST>r i AM-Taiwan     12-05 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taiwan,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Forced to Recount Votes After Fraud Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Results of recount expected after 7 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nationalist government Tuesday was
forced to agree to recount an important race after the ruling
party's victory drew allegations of fraud and led to a clash
between police and opposition supporters.
   In Taipei, newspaper reports said about 12 percent of the votes
cast in Saturday's island-wide election were bogus. Central
Election Commission officials refused comment on the reports.
   The vote, the first multiparty election in Taiwan's history,
dealt the Nationalist Party its worst setback in 40 years in power.
Nationalists lost several important local elections and garnered 58
percent of the total vote, down from 70 percent in 1986.
   During the election and raucous campaign, the opposition party
accused the Nationalists of widespread vote buying and ballot box
stuffing.
   Those allegations were strongest in Tainan, a largely
agricultural county in southern Taiwan, where a Nationalist and an
opposition Democratic Progressive Party candidate were in a close
race for the county executive post, one of the highest elected
offices in Taiwan.
   About 10,000 opposition supporters screaming for a recount
packed a square next to county government offices in Tainan on
Tuesday.
   Club-wielding protesters discovered five plainclothes policemen
in their midst and beat them, police said. The officers, disguised
as journalists, were stripped of their cameras, which were tossed
into a nearby swimming pool, police said.
   Police grabbed and beat one protester with clubs.
   Witnesses said several protesters were injured. Police said at
least two people were hospitalized.
   The crowd soon swelled as thousands of protesters armed with
clubs and stones flocked to the square. About 2,000 riot police
cordoned off the square and set up water cannons.
   Huang Hsin-chieh, chairman of the opposition Democratic
Progressive Party, went to Tainan and asked the county government
for a recount of the roughly 200,000 votes.
   After hours of negotiations, the government agreed to a recount
in the presence of opposition officials. Officials said the outcome
would be known Wednesday.
   According to official results, Nationalist candidate Lee
Ya-chiao defeated opposition candidate Lee Tsung-fan by 9,000 votes.
   County executives wield wide powers over police, schools and the
economy of their constituencies and are among the highest elected
officials here.
   In Saturday's voting, the opposition won six of 15 county
executive seats, not including the controversial Tainan seat. In
1986, the opposition won two.
   In the capital, newspaper reports said 814,000 votes were
invalidated. Fewer than 7 million people voted.
   In the central city of Nantou, about 400 demonstrators ended an
overnight sit-in Tuesday after authorities promised an
investigation of alleged vote buying.
   A Nationalist official, Wu Tun-yi, said he would ``disembowel
myself if there was any vote rigging.''
</TEXT>
