<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Czechoslovakia     12-05 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Czechoslovakia,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mazowiecki Returns From First Warsaw Pact Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki said
Tuesday he was glad the Warsaw Pact alliance has condemned its 1968
invasion of Czechoslovakia.
   Mazowiecki, a Solidarity activist and former political prisoner,
on Monday became the first non-communist government chief to take
part in a Warsaw Pact summit. He represented Poland at the meeting
in Moscow along with communist President Wojciech Jaruzelski and
non-communist Foreign Minister Krzysztof Skubiszewski.
   The meeting, held as tumultuous reforms spread through the East
bloc, included a briefing from President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on
the weekend summit with President Bush in Malta.
   Mazowiecki, a Roman Catholic, said in an interview with the
state PAP news agency that Gorbachev also expressed ``high
respect'' for Polish-born Pope John Paul II, with whom he had an
unprecedented meeting in Rome on Friday.
   ``Mr. Gorbachev put a great emphasis on the fact that it had
been a very, very interesting meeting for him,'' Mazowiecki said.
   Jaruzelski, commenting to PAP on the Warsaw Pact meeting, said:
``It is true the participants were different to a large extent _
the leaderships have changed in many countries. Of course, we were
aware that our foreign policy is being pursued in new conditions,
in a period of changes taking place today in nearly all socialist
countries.''
   Skubiszewski praised the resolution that criticized the 1968
Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia. He said the Polish
delegation successfully moved to have the resolution include a
section saying ``the Warsaw Treaty is no grounds for any
intervention in the internal affairs of states.''
   ``I am glad that this could take place at the first meeting of
the Warsaw Treaty states' leaders in which I had an opportunity to
participate,'' Mazowiecki said of the resolution.
   The prime minister, who last month made his first official trip
to the Soviet Union, has promised his government will remain loyal
to the Warsaw Pact alliance.
</TEXT>
