<FILEID>AP-PX-12-05-89 1407EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     12-05 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dec. 18 Launch Set for Space Shuttle Columbia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA on Tuesday set Dec. 18 for
launching space shuttle Columbia on a 10-day Christmas flight, but
said liftoff could be delayed a day or two if a renovated launch
pad is not ready.
   Liftoff was scheduled for 7:29 p.m., the second straight
after-dark shuttle launch. It also would be the third flight in
three months, the sixth this year and would tie the longest
previous shuttle mission.
   Columbia's five-person crew is to deploy a Navy communications
satellite and then track down and retrieve for return to Earth a
science satellite that has orbited Earth nearly six years.
   Dec. 18, which has been a launch target for some time, became
official at the conclusion of a two-day flight readiness review by
shuttle managers.
   A statement announcing the date noted that a new mobile launch
platform and a modified launch pad 39A are being used for the first
time.
   ``Due to work on these facilities, there is a higher than normal
probability of developing problems that might result in a short
delay to the launch date,'' the statement said.
   Minor problems have cropped up in fitting the shuttle to the new
facilities since Columbia moved to the pad last week.
   ``We've got a good shot at making the 18th if the pad work goes
smoothly,'' said space agency spokesman Ed Campion. He said if
problems do crop up, he expected the delay would be minimal, ``a
day or two.''
   Pad 39A was the launch base for the first 24 shuttle missions,
but has not been used in nearly four years. Workers recently
completed a two-year, $50 million overhaul to improve safety,
electrical, fuel line, environmental control and other systems.
   All seven launches since shuttle flights resumed 15 months ago
have been from neighboring pad 39B. The program was grounded for 32
months after the 1986 Challenger explosion.
   If there were a delay of several days, shuttle managers
discussed options to avoid launching on Christmas Day so most
workers could have the holiday off. Campion said under study are a
plan to launch a day or two after Christmas and another that would
put the flight off until after New Year's Day.
   Astronaut Dan Brandenstein will command Columbia's crew. The
others are pilot Jim Wetherbee and mission specialists Bonnie
Dunbar, Marsha Ivins and David Low.
</TEXT>
