<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Politics     12-05 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Politics,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Survives Leadership Challenge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher today comfortably
defeated an unprecedented challenge to her leadership of the
Conservative Party, but failed to crush all traces of rebellion.
   She got the votes of 314 of her 374 members of Parliament, while
33 opposed her and 24 abstained. Three failed to vote.
   That meant 57 lawmakers, or 15 percent, refused to support her,
and the figure provoked conflicting initial assessments.
   ``Anything below 50 would have been an absolute triumph. I think
57 is a bloody good result,'' said Norman Tebbit, a Thatcher ally
and former party chairman.
   ``I think it is a troublesome result for her,'' said John Cole,
BBC-TV's political editor, broadcasting the result live to the
nation from the House of Commons.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who has been re-elected unopposed every year
since she became party leader in 1974, was challenged by Sir
Anthony Meyer, 69, a little-known outsider who put up his candidacy
to rally anti-Thatcher sentiment.
   The consensus had been that if 100 or more failed to support
her, Mrs. Thatcher would have been badly damaged, while anything
under 45 would be an unassailable vote of confidence in her.
   Meyer conceded that the prime minister, already 10 years in
office, was entitled to feel ``pretty pleased with the result.''
   Meyer had sought to rally opposition to Mrs. Thatcher's handling
of the economy, her tough style of leadership, and her reluctance
to integrate Britain deeper into the European Economic Community.
   Mrs. Thatcher has run unopposed in the annual vote since she
ousted Edward Heath as party leader after the Tories lost the 1974
general election to the Labor Party.
   She came to power when the Conservatives won the 1979 general
election. She is in her third term as prime minister following Tory
victories in the 1983 and 1987 general elections. She is the
longest serving prime minister this century.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
