<SECOND>AM-City Employment,100</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Employment Sets Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release 6:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's cities employed a record
2,570,103 workers as of October 1988, the Census Bureau said
Tuesday.
   That is 28,735 more employees than worked for cities a year
earlier and about 9,000 more than the previous record, set in 1980.
   Payrolls for city employees totaled about $5 billion, up 6.2
percent from 1987, with full-time employees averaging $2,270 a
month.
   While the bureau counted 19,200 municipal governments, 58
percent of employees worked for the 270 cities with populations of
75,000 or more.
   Police accounted for the largest single category of city
employees, at 399,822, followed by education, 333,325; local
utilities, 227,170, and fire protection, 196,977.
