<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Julio Iglesias is said to be near settlement
with the security guard who claims the singer felled him with a
karate chop in 1986.
   A civil trial for damages was scheduled Monday in U.S. District
Court here, but a lawyer for the guard asked that the trial be
called off saying the case was close to settlement.
   David Wells, a lawyer representing Iglesias, said the settlement
was ``in the works. But I don't see any reason that it won't be
worked out.''
   The guard, Stephen A. Clemons, claims that Iglesias made racial
comments to Clemons and another guard at a St. Louis hotel, then
followed the verbal attack with a karate chop on the neck.
   Iglesias has denied striking Clemons, saying he merely greeted
him in a friendly manner.
   Clemons originally sought $50,000 in actual damages and $250,000
in punitive damages. He amended the lawsuit in January to seek $5
million in punitive damages.
