<FIRST>r a AM-Library-Jail     12-05 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Library-Jail,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Sues for $500,000 Over Being Jailed in Overdue Book Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman jailed for having seven overdue library
books is suing the county and its solicitor for $500,000.
   Karen Lindsay, a 48-year-old office worker from suburban
Atlanta, was jailed overnight in October for failing to appear in
court on the overdue-book charges. She said she returned the books
in 1988 and was never served with the notice to appear in court.
   ``That seems like a reasonable amount for being dragged out of
your house at 10:30 p.m. and spending a night in jail without
bond,'' said Herbert P. Schlanger, Ms. Lindsay's attorney.
   The U.S. District Court complaint alleges false arrest.
   Schlanger said that because Ms. Lindsay never received court
notice, she committed no crime and, therefore, was falsely
imprisoned.
   Solicitor Gerald N. Blaney, named in the lawsuit, declined
comment, but has acknowledged that the woman didn't receive the
notice.
   Ms. Lindsay is to appear Thursday night on ``The Tonight Show
Starring Johnny Carson'' to talk about her experience.
   She said Monday that she hopes the lawsuit will result in a
change in the policy of issuing arrest warrants for people who
haven't received notice to appear in court.
</TEXT>
