<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionReferrals     12-05 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Referrals,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Challenges Ban On Abortion Referrals In U.S.-Paid Clinics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government is trying to turn family
planning clinics into venues for anti-abortion advocacy,
Massachusetts' attorney general argued Tuesday in appealing a ban
on abortion service referrals for clinics receiving government
funds.
   In 1988, the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services barred
family planning clinics from suggesting abortion as an option to
pregnancy. It specifically prohibits use of federal money for
programs that assist women in obtaining abortions. It also bans the
use of funding for activities that ``encourage, promote or advocate
abortion.''
   The regulation is on hold while Massachusetts, New York and
Colorado wage court battles against it, claiming it violates
constitutional rights of privacy and free speech.
   ``These regulations suppress one viewpoint but foist on patients
another viewpoint _ that she should carry that pregnancy to term,''
Massachusetts Attorney General James Shannon argued Tuesday before
the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. ``What we're talking about
here is government manipulating information.''
   He presented a scenario in which poor, uneducated, pregnant
women leave a family planning clinic believing they must continue
their pregnancy with no alternative.
   ``The government doesn't have to subsidize a constitutional
right (to abortion), but it can't interfere with these rights,''
Shannon said.
   Arguments Tuesday invoked both the 1973 Supreme Court decision
in Roe vs. Wade that abortion is a woman's right to decide and the
so-called Webster case in July that said a state can deny funding
for abortions.
   Justice Department counsel Alfred Mollin, arguing for Health and
Human Services, said Webster established ``it is wrong for the
government to place an obstacle, but not wrong to leave an obstacle
there.''
   Mollin contended that the regulations are not as prohibitive as
they seem.
   They don't prevent a clinic staff from at least saying they
don't make abortion referrals, he said. He also said a physician
can still refer a woman for an abortion if the pregnancy risks her
life or health.
   ``The tone of the regulations are not to set up an anti-abortion
advocacy group,'' Mollin said.
   The matter has already been before the court in Boston. In May,
three judges of the 1st Circuit ruled in favor of the state,
upholding an injunction blocking the ban on referrals from taking
effect.
   But when the Supreme Court handed down the Webster decision two
months later, the federal government asked the 1st Circuit to
rehear the arguments in this new light.
   Elsewhere, the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New York
City upheld the regulations last month.
   A ruling is pending on an appeal of the regulations in federal
court in Denver on behalf of Planned Parenthood affiliates.
   This fiscal year, the federal government is spending $138
million to provide family planning services to 5 million teen-agers
and women.
   ``This case is the only one that is national in scope,'' said
Scott Swirling, executive director of the National Family Planning
and Reproductive Health Association based in Washington, D.C. ``The
outcome will determine whether poor women can get complete amounts
of information (about abortion).
   ``This case doesn't concern the legality of abortion, but until
and unless the Supreme Court overturns Roe v. Wade, abortion is a
legal and constitutional right.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
