<DOCNO> AP891205-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-05-89 1528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bennett-Drugs     12-05 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett-Drugs,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Sees `Happy Ending' to Budget Battle Between Bennett, Darman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a report that national drug policy
director William J. Bennett and budget director Richard Darman are
at loggerheads over the 1991 budget to fight illegal drugs, a
Bennett spokesman said Tuesday that he expects ``a happy ending''
when the shouting is over.
   An administration source said Monday that ``Bennett and Darman
are apart by more than a couple of hundred million dollars. It may
end up going to the president to get things sorted out.''
   The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, refused to
detail the proposals from Bennett or Darman but did say he expects
to see ``a real increase'' over the $8.8 billion 1991 budget.
   Under the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988 which created Bennett's
Office of National Drug Control Policy, Bennett is required to
certify that the anti-drug budget sent to Capitol Hill is adequate
to fund the strategy he has developed to curb drug use.
   After President Bush presented the original strategy Sept. 5,
along with a $7.9 billion price tag for 1990, members of Congress
questioned Bennett on whether he had set the budget figure or
whether that figure had been imposed by Darman's Office of
Management and Budget. Bennett told Congress _ which eventually
increased the 1990 budget to $8.8 billion _ that he felt the $7.9
billion was adequate.
   Asked if Bennett would be able to give Congress the same
assurances on the 1991 budget if he doesn't win the battle with
Darman, Bennett spokesman Don Hamilton said Tuesday, ``I'm not
really very worried about it. I'm confident it's all going to have
a happy ending.
   ``The agencies come up with the numbers,'' Hamilton said.
``Bennett takes a look at them. The idea is that we work this
through, keeping OMB in what should be a three-cornered thing.''
   Hamilton had said Monday, ``This is the time of year when lots
of agency heads and Cabinet secretaries are talking to Darman,
occasionally in strong terms.''
   OMB spokeswoman Barbara Clay said only, ``We have nothing to
say. We don't comment at all on the '91 budget, and this falls into
that category.''
   Meanwhile, Bennett's office is continuing to work on the update
of the national drug control strategy, referred to among officials
as ``Strategy Two.'' Like the original strategy, the update is
required by Congress.
   The update is expected to include designations of cities or
regions considered ``high-intensity drug-trafficking areas'' that
would be eligible for additional federal resources, both money and
personnel.
   Published reports have said the areas to be so designated in the
upcoming strategy are Los Angeles, New York, Miami, Houston and the
Southwest border. Officials in Bennett's office say no final
decisions have been made.
   ``The conversations in reference to high-intensity drug
trafficking areas are still ongoing,'' said Reggie Walton,
associate director for state and local affairs. ``It is incorrect
to say any final resolutions have been made.
   Although numerous cities have clamored for the designation in
the hope of a windfall of federal aid, there is relatively little
money available for 1990. Only $25 million is in the federal
budget, and that could be enhanced by up to $21 million from the
federal asset forfeiture fund, Walton said. That fund contains
revenue from assets seized from drug traffickers, including cash,
bank accounts, homes, cars, planes and boats, among other things.
   But one administration official said, ``We're looking at
dividing this money up among four, five, six, seven areas. What can
you do with this money?'' The official said the Los Angeles area
spends $2 billion of its own money for anti-drug efforts.
   In comparison, Bennett has said the federal effort to crack down
on drugs in the nation's capital alone will cost about $97 million,
including money for three drug treatment centers and a new jail for
the District of Columbia.
   Walton said the high-intensity drug-trafficking areas might get
federal resources such as personnel instead of cash. He declined to
say how much money would be sought for the areas in 1991.
</TEXT>
