<FIRST>r a AM-Marijuana-Teacher     12-05 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marijuana-Teacher,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Teacher of Year Files Federal Lawsuit Over Job Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALDOSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Teacher of the Year acquitted of
drug charges that resulted in her firing has sued to get her job
back.
   Vicki Sherling, who was arrested along with her husband,
Michael, after authorities found marijuana plants in a makeshift
greenhouse in the couple's yard, also seeks an unspecified amount
of damages in the lawsuit filed Monday in U.S. District Court.
   The former teacher in Moultrie in southwest Georgia was
temporarily suspended from her job in May, shortly after being
arrested. In June, the school board dismissed her and the State
Board of Education upheld the local board.
   An appeal of that decision is in the state courts, said her
lawyer, William Norwood.
   Sherling pleaded guilty to possessing and manufacturing
marijuana and drew a 10-year sentence with three years to serve. He
testified in court that Mrs. Sherling had no knowledge of the
plants.
   The lawsuit contends that many of the school board members
``prejudged the case'' and that Mrs. Sherling was denied due
process of law because the board was not impartial.
   The lawsuit also contends that Mrs. Sherling, Colquitt County's
Teacher of the Year for 1989, was told that she was not fired
because of the drug charges, but because she ``allowed her husband
to use marijuana.''
</TEXT>
