<FIRST>u w BC-Scotus-Glance 1stLd-Writethru   12-05 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Scotus-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0610,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf of final section ``TAXIS'' to CORRECT ``states
and cities'' to ``cities and other local governments.'' Ruling does not
apply to states</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Tuesday by the Supreme Court.
   
   LAWYERS SANCTIONS
   
   The court ruled that federal judges may punish lawyers but not
their law firms for frivolous lawsuits and needless legal maneuvers.
   Voting 8-1 to overturn a $50,000 penalty against a now-dissolved
New York City law firm, the justices said a federal court rule is
aimed only at the lawyers who sign the offending documents. The
rule does not apply to those lawyers' law firms, the court said.
   The rule at issue says courts may deal with an offending
document by imposing ``on the person who signed it ... an
appropriate sanction.''
   The case is Pavelic &amp; LeFlore vs. Marvel Entertainment, 88-791.
   
   UNIONS
   
   The court made it easier for workers to sue their unions over
alleged failures to offer fair representation.
   The justices unanimously reinstated a federal lawsuit a Toledo,
Ohio, area sheet metal worker filed against his union five years
ago.
   Lower courts had thrown out the suit, ruling the plaintiff was
alleging an unfair labor practice and that the National Labor
Relations Board has exclusive jurisdiction over such claims. The
justices said those courts were wrong.
   The case is Breininger vs. Sheet Metal Workers, 88-124.
   
   TAXIS
   
   The court ruled that cities and other local governments that
interfere illegally in labor negotiations may be forced to pay
damages for losses suffered by management or workers.
   The court ruled, 6-3, that Los Angeles officials are required to
compensate a taxi company that went out of business after the city
interfered in a dispute between the company and its driver.
   The case is Golden State Transit vs. Los Angeles, 88-840.
</TEXT>
