<FIRST>u i AM-Spain-Politics     12-05 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Politics,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gonzalez Confirmed for 3rd Term as Spanish Prime Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Felipe Gonzalez won parliamentary approval
on the first ballot Tuesday for his third-straight term as Spain's
prime minister.
   A total of 167 lower-house deputies voted in favor of the
Socialist leader, the bare-minimum majority necessary for first
ballot confirmation.
   Due to court rulings annuling the Oct. 29 election of 18
deputies in three voting districts, the number of deputies in the
lower house, or Cortes, has been reduced temporarily to 332 from
350.
   All 166 of the Socialist deputies voted for Gonzalez, along with
Luis Mardones, the sole deputy of the Independent Coalition of the
Canary Islands. Another 155 deputies voted against Gonzalez and six
abstained.
   Four other deputies-elect, who belong to the Herri Batasuna
Party, considered the political wing of the armed Basque separatist
group ETA, were not eligible to vote after refusing Monday to swear
allegiance to the Spanish constitution.
   Without the support of at least one non-Socialist deputy,
Gonzalez would have had to wait 48 hours for probable confirmation
with a plurality on a second ballot.
   The courts have ordered repeat elections by March in the North
African enclave of Melilla, and the provinces of Murcia and
Pontevedra.
   Gonzalez told parliament Monday he would call for a vote of
confidence once all 350 deputies are elected.
   The 47-year-old former labor lawyer has headed the Socialist
Party since 1974. He was elected to four-year terms in 1982 and
1986.
   Spaniards vote for party slates under a system of proportional
representation based on results tabulated in the 52 electoral
districts.
</TEXT>
