<FIRST>r a AM-ABCAx     12-05 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ABC Ax,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC Cancels Two Series</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC, which canceled Jackie Mason's ``Chicken
Soup'' last month, on Tuesday canceled two more new series,
``Homeroom'' and ``Living Dolls,'' and added two new series, one an
NBC castoff.
   ABC also said it is moving ``Mission: Impossible'' from
Thursdays to Saturdays as of Jan. 6, and taking ``Mr. Belvedere''
off the air after the show's Dec. 30 telecast. It will bring that
show back later this season.
   ABC's new series are ``Father Dowling Mysteries,'' starring Tom
Bosley as a crime-solving priest, and the self-explanatory
``America's Funniest Home Videos,'' which had strong ratings as a
Nov. 26 special.
   Bosley's series, which NBC aired last year, now will air
Thursdays on ABC, and debut on Jan. 4. ABC's other new show will
premiere Jan. 14, when ABC's new ``Free Spirit'' also will be moved
up by a half-hour to a new 8:30 p.m. EST time period Sundays.
   The two canceled ABC series were among last week's lowest-rated
network shows. The network's changes raised to seven the number of
new network shows dropped since the season began in September. NBC
earlier canceled ``Nutt House,'' and CBS axed ``The People Next
Door,'' ``Peaceable Kingdom'' and ``Top of the Hill.''
