<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru a0661 12-05 0843</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0661,0865</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czech Republic Names Government With Non-Communist Majority</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with party labor union endorsing strike, work
on demolishing border fences to begin, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of Czechoslovakia's two
republics named the first government in 41 years dominated by
non-Communists, and talks began with opposition leaders on their
demands for a new national government.
   Leaders of the Communist-controlled labor organization took the
unprecedented step of endorsing a general strike that the
opposition has threatened if the national government is not changed
this week.
   An Interior Ministry announcement said work on dismantling
fortifications on the border with Austria would begin Monday. The
government said last week some of the barbed wire, watch towers and
trip wires would be taken down.
   About 2,000 demonstrating students chanted ``Resign! Resign!''
as Ladislav Adamec, the Communist premier, met with dissident
playwright Vaclav Havel on demands for a new Cabinet to replace the
Communist-dominated one chosen Sunday.
   Jiri Dienstbier, spokesman for Havel's opposition group, Civic
Forum, said the discussions would continue Wednesday. Miroslav
Pavel, who is head of state television and attended the talks, said
they were ``very complicated.''
   Opposition groups say the general strike will take place Monday
unless the 21-member Cabinet, which contains only five
non-Communists, is replaced before then.
   Dienstbier called the new Czech government ``a step in the right
direction,'' but said its composition still was not an accurate
reflection of public opinion.
   The parliamentary commission investigating the police violence
Nov. 17 that started the nation's peaceful revolt, said Tuesday
that ousted Communist Party chief Milos Jakes and Miroslav Stepan,
the former Prague party boss, ``bear direct political
responsibility'' for the crackdown.
   It proposed that six senior police officers be fired to prevent
them influencing the investigation.
   The Czech cabinet named to serve under Premier Frantisek Pitra,
a Communist, includes nine non-Communists and seven members of the
party. It is the first government of any kind in Czechoslovakia
since 1948 not to be dominated by Communists.
   Two ministers are from the Socialist Party and two from the
People's Party, both of which had been docile allies of the
Communists but are playing an increasingly independent role.
   After the government was announced, the People's Party demanded
an immediate change to give non-Communists more power. It also
demanded the party relinquish control of the Czech interior
ministry, which oversees the regional police.
   In a statement, the party said it wants 50 percent of cabinet
posts given to non-party experts, with the Communists and two other
parties sharing the other half.
   Dienstbier said Civic Forum endorsed the People's Party demands.
   Under Czechoslovakia's federal system, the Czech and Slovak
governments have responsibility for several areas in which the
opposition wants reforms, such as education, justice and culture.
Communists still dominate the Slovak regional government.
   Miroslav Toman, first deputy prime minister of the Czech
government, defended retention by Communists of the Interior
Ministry and other key portfolios such as finance, agriculture and
industry by suggesting other parties did not necessarily have
qualified candidates.
   Asked how soon the regional government wanted free elections, a
central demand of the opposition, he said it favored ``very swift
adoption'' of a new law.
   Late Tuesday, the regional party released the text of its
program for economic and political reform. Central Commitee member
Jan Siroky described it as ``a platform for the revival of the
Communist Party from the grassroots.''
   Hundreds of thousands of people took to the streets Monday to
protest the new national Cabinet, which includes 16 Communists and
many holdovers from the last government. They also called for free
elections by July.
   The opposition has won astounding concessions from the
Communists since protests of police suppression of peaceful
demonstrators Nov. 17 led to a mass movement for democracy.
   Adamec agreed last week to name a new coalition government and
relinquish the party's 41-year hold on power. A day later,
Parliament voted to remove consitutional provisions that gave the
party a power monopoly.
   At Monday's rally, Vaclav Maly, an opposition spokesman, was
cheered loudly when he said Civic Forum and its Slovak counterpart,
Public Against Violence, would run candidates when free elections
are held.
   More cheers went up when other opposition members demanded the
truth about the Warsaw Pact invasion that crushed the ``Prague
Spring'' of reform in 1968.
   After the national Communist Party reversed 21 years of policy
Friday and declared the invasion a mistake, it was officially
condemned Monday by the Soviet Union and the four other Warsaw Pact
nations who participated. The statement was printed without comment
in official Czechoslovak dailies Tuesday.
   In a nationally televised address, national party leader Karel
Urbanek said he discussed the ``tragic events of August 1968'' with
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev at the Warsaw Pact meeting
Monday in Moscow.
   ``The new party leadership fully identified itself with the
inspirational sources of the Prague Spring,'' Urbanek declared. He
said the party's new action program calls for the political
rehabilitation of those expelled from the party after the invasion.
</TEXT>
