<FIRST>r w AM-Obit-Ordman     12-05 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Ordman,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Labor Board Official Dies At 77</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arnold Ordman, who served two terms as general
counsel to the National Labor Relations board and later as an
administrative law judge and arbitrator, died of heart failure
Tuesday at a Maryland hospital. He was 77.
   Ordman, of Bethesda, Md., was the only person to serve two
successive terms as NLRB general counsel, serving under Presidents
Kennedy and Johnson. He had joined the agency in 1946 as a member
of its legal staff.
   He became an administrative law judge in 1971 and four years
later left that post to establish a private arbitration practice.
He also lectured on law and labor issues at several law schools.
   Ordman, a native of Somersworth, N.H., graduated from Boston
University and Harvard Law School. He served in the Navy during
World War II as a signal officer aboard the USS York.
</TEXT>
