<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0630 12-05 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0630,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Tells West Germany Reunification Talk Stirs Trouble</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with new material and editing, UPDATING with
Shevardnadze warning Genscher regarding German reunification. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union sharply warned West Germany at a
meeting of their foreign ministers on Tuesday that pushing for
German reunification at this time can only bring trouble, the
Soviet news agency Tass reported.
   It said Eduard Shevardnadze recalled Soviet experience with a
strong Germany during World War II in telling Hans-Dietrich
Genscher ``propaganda about a federation of the two Germanys can
only exacerbate turmoil in the current circumstances.''
   The official news agency quoted Shevardnadze as saying:
   ``An attempt to use difficulties in the reconstruction process
in socialist countries for one-sided, selfish goals, without taking
into account the long-term general European interests, can threaten
the accumulated positive developments, stability and peace on the
continent.''
   Genscher also met Tuesday with President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to
discuss what was once unthinkable for the Soviets: German
reunification.
   Following the defeat of Adolf Hitler's Nazi Germany, the German
state became divided into two nations _ communist East Germany, in
the Soviet sphere, and capitalistic, pro-Western West Germany.
   At the weekend summit in Malta, Gorbachev told President Bush
that ``reunification gave the Soviet Union some problems that could
push it too hard, too fast, could create some real tension,''
according to Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   Genscher told a news conference later he assured Gorbachev both
Germanys ``will keep in mind their responsibility for the security
of the whole of Europe.''
   For the Soviet Union, which says it lost 20 million people to
the Nazis in the war, theoretical queries on the prospect of a
reunited Germany have long brought flat rejection.
   Shevardnadze told Genscher, ``The current developments touch on
deep-rooted interests of the Soviet Union, the countries of the
Warsaw Pact and finally all Europeans. The Soviet people well
remember history and the tragic lesson of the Second World War. Our
public opinion is sensitive to everything relating to its result.
No one should forget this.''
   Gorbachev in recent weeks has tempered his previous clear
opposition as political upheaval in East Germany brought the
question to the forefront of international discussion, and West
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl offered a detailed process for
possible reunification.
   While objecting to any immediate call for reunification,
Gorbachev has indicated a willingness to let history decide.
   Tass said Monday that, ``Despite the acuteness of the problem,
the Soviet Union is prepared to discuss it in the spirit of new
thinking, presupposing respect for the stand of the other.''
   But according to Tass, Shevardnadze's side of the discussion
that resulted was strongly worded. He said some of the 10 points in
Kohl's reunification plan sounded like orders to East Germany,
``demanding irreversible changes in its political and economic
system.''
   A separate Tass report on Gorbachev's comment to Genscher was
far milder. The president said that under the present circumstances
of rapid change in Europe and improving relations between East and
West, ``it is especially important to support international
stability and to strengthen security,'' Tass reported.
   ``This suggests self-restraint, responsibility and deliberation
in actions from all states, and loyal cooperation on the basis of
generally accepted principles,'' Tass added, paraphrasing Gorbachev.
   Genscher told reporters that he assured Gorbachev, ``There is
not going to be a separate German course.''
   He said German rapprochement will occur only within general
European rapprochement, and ``we will do everything to create
stable, cooperative structures'' to ensure the security of Europe.
   Genscher refused to discuss Gorbachev's response.
   Tass also said that Genscher and Shevardnadze shared their
desires to reach agreements on the reduction of strategic offensive
weapons and conventional armed forces, and on a ban on chemical
weapons.
</TEXT>
