<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--AlienStory     12-05 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Alien Story,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bogus Story of Aliens in Rockford Gets Newspaper Worked Fired</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKFORD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A phony article saying aliens claiming to
be human children were seen near this northern Illinois city
appeared on the front page of the Rockford Register Star.
   The story ran only four lines and was at the bottom of the page
in several thousand copies of a Sunday edition. It was written by a
production worker as a practical joke, USA Today reported Tuesday.
   The newspaper printed a retraction Monday.
   Publisher Michael Coleman did not return several telephone
messages Tuesday from The Associated Press. His secretary, Sonna
Shook, said he was in meetings and unavailable for comment.
   ``These aliens claim to be human children offering further proof
that alien beings do indeed live in our planet and may be among
local residents,'' the article said. Its headline said ``Aliens
Spotted Near Rockford.''
   The worker mistakenly put the article on a page cleared for
printing and has been fired, USA Today reported. The presses were
stopped when the item was noticed, but early editions had already
been delivered.
