<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--People-Thurmond     12-05 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--People-Thurmond,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress' Oldest Member, Sen. Strom Thurmond, Turns 87</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, the oldest
member of Congress, celebrated his 87th birthday Tuesday, saying
the secret of a long life is a good diet, exercise and optimism.
   ``If a person follows that, then they will have a chance to live
a happier life and help humanity,'' said the Republican lawmaker,
who has represented South Carolina in the Senate for 35 years.
   Thurmond said he watches his diet and exercises 50 minutes each
morning, doing calisthenics, lifting weights and riding a
stationary bicycle. He said he also tries to keep an optimistic
outlook on life.
   He came to this city just northwest of Charleston with U.S.
Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner to announce a $32 million
emergency grant for repairs to highways damaged by Hurricane Hugo.
   Thurmond planned to return to Washington later in the day for a
small party with his staff.
</TEXT>
