<FIRST>r a AM-Addict-Monastery     12-05 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Addict-Monastery,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge to Addict: ``Get Thee to a Monastery''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARDENBERGH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A longtime heroin user has accepted a
judge's offer to spend two years in a Zen Buddhist monastery
instead of going through a drug treatment program.
   Loudoun County (Va.) Circuit Judge James Chamblin on Monday gave
Keith Brian Scofield of Sterling, Va., the option of going through
his sixth drug treatment program or entering the Zen Studies
Society Mountain Monastery in Ulster County, about 70 miles
northwest of New York City.
   ``Conventional drug treatment sure doesn't produce many
winners,'' Scofield said Tuesday in a telephone interview from
Loudoun County Jail in Virginia. ``I've been to some of the best in
the country and believe me they just don't work.''
   After his release from the previous drug programs, ``I lasted
about a week'' before he went back on drugs, he said.
   The monastery's acting abbot, Junpo Dennis Kelly, said Scofield
is the first criminal drug user the retreat has agreed to take in.
But Kelly said several of the 20 people living at the monastery
turned to Buddhism to overcome drug addiction.
   ``In the '60s and '70s I experimented with a lot of drugs,''
experiences that should help him understand Scofield's problem,
Kelly said. ``I know right where he's coming from.''
   Scofield, 30, was convicted in November 1988 of heroin
possession and released on probation. He was arrested on a petty
larceny charge last June, and Chamblin sentenced him to five years
in prison for violating probation.
   All but six months of that sentence was suspended because
Chamblin planned to order Scofield to undergo drug treatment, said
Paul Maslakowski, Scofield's attorney.
   On Monday, Chamblin agreed to Scofield's request to let him
spend two years at the monastery instead of going through drug
treatment.
   ``The judge said `Get thee to a nunnery,''' said court
spokeswoman Fay Payne.
   While visiting Scofield in jail, his brother joked that ``they
ought to send me to a monastery instead of a drug treatment
center,'' he said. ``We laughed about it, but later when I was back
upstairs reading, I thought that ... I'd give it a try.''
   Scofield said he has been reading books on Zen Buddhism for
about a year. He said he has had a drug problem off and on since he
was 13.
   If Scofield violates monastery rules or leaves the retreat
before his two years are up, he probably will be sent back to jail,
Maslakowski said.
   ``It puts a lot of pressure on Keith,'' Maslakowski said ``When
a judge gives a guy a break like this, he doesn't have much
sympathy if he shows up before him again.''
   Probation officers will be allowed into the monastery to check
on Scofield, he said.
   Scofield will be released into the custody of his mother,
Josephine Regis, who will take him to the monastery, probably by
this weekend, Maslakowski said.
   His routine at the 1,400-acre retreat will include rising at
4:30 a.m., hard work through most of the day, vegetarian meals
eaten in silence, periods of meditation and intensive study of
philosophy, Kelly said.
   Scofield is a carpenter by trade, and his skills will come in
handy on repairs to monastery buildings and cutting firewood for
the retreat's boilers, Kelly said.
</TEXT>
