<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 1756EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Summit-Aftermath 1stLd-Writethru a0694 12-05 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Aftermath, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0694,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Concessions at Summit; Now the Fine Print</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 7th graf, He was ... to include that Bush wants U.S.-Soviet
chemical deal by June Summit; SUBS 12th graf, Administration lawyers ...
to substitute word ``approve'' for ``ratify.''</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP New Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush made three concessions at the
Malta summit that were overshadowed in the euphoria and confusion
surrounding the first-ever joint U.S.-Soviet presidential news
conference.
   Those steps met longstanding Soviet requests and marked a
political milestone for a man who had reacted cautiously to the
reforms of Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Administration officials said Tuesday, however, that the fine
print still needed to be written on Bush's offers involving the
lifting of trade sanctions against Moscow and a halt in U.S.
production of chemical weapons.
   Although the summit produced no clear arms control
breakthroughs, and was not expected to, Bush gave Gorbachev these
welcome bits of news:
   _He would take steps to ease tariffs on Soviet exports to
America.
   _He would seek observer status for the Kremlin in a major
international trade group.
   _He was altering his previous, and for the Soviets unpalatable,
proposal on chemical weapons, seeking to sign a treaty for the June
summit to destroy most U.S. and Soviet chemical weapons stockpiles.
   Several major U.S. and Soviet steps are necessary before Bush
grants the Soviet Union most-favored-nation status, easing tariffs
on Soviet imports to the United States.
   First, the United States and the Soviets must reach a commercial
treaty, said a U.S. official who expects the American side ``to be
in talks with the Soviets in the next six or eight weeks.'' Bush
proposed that he and Gorbachev sign such a treaty at the summit
they are planning in America in the last two weeks of June.
   Second, Bush must waive provisions of a 1974 law that barred
most-favored-nation status for the Soviet Union until the Kremlin
eased its emigration policies. Soviet authorities have relaxed the
rules, and the emigration of Jews and other minorities is headed
for record levels this year.
   At Malta, however, Bush told Gorbachev he would not waive the
1974 law until the Soviet parliament passes legislation giving the
new emigration rules greater permanence, and the parliament is not
due back in session until late January.
   Administration lawyers say Bush can waive the law without
consulting Congress, but it is not clear whether the Senate or the
full Congress must approve a U.S.-Soviet commercial treaty,
according to U.S. officials who spoke on condition they not be
further identified.
   Once the sanctions are waived and the treaty signed, Bush plans
to ask Congress to lift a $300 million ceiling that it imposed on
U.S. government loans to the Soviet Union.
   Obtaining observer status for the Soviets on the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade may be just as complex.
   Bush told Gorbachev he wanted Moscow to study GATT to encourage
greater Soviet ``engagement with the international market economy.''
   Common Market leaders already have advocated Soviet observer
status in the 97-nation GATT, a status already enjoyed by Hungary
and China.
   The concession that Bush made on chemical weapons was designed
to speed progress on bilateral as well multilateral treaties,
officials said.
   Last September at the United Nations, Bush offered to destroy 80
percent of U.S. chemical weapon stockpiles if the Soviets reduced
to the same level. Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
responded that his country was willing to destroy all its chemical
weapons.
   Further controversy developed over Bush's statement that the
United States planned to retain 2 percent of its chemical weapons
until the 10th year of a proposed multilateral convention calling
upon all nations to destroy their stocks within a decade.
   Administration officials later confirmed that this provision
meant that the United States would continue to make a new
generation of chemical weapons even after the multilateral
convention was signed, a provision that drew criticism from Moscow
and other capitals.
   Moreover, Bush said, the United States would not destroy its
last chemical weapons until all nations able to produce chemical
weapons signed the multilateral treaty, which is still under
negotiation.
   At Malta, Bush told Gorbachev he was willing to end U.S.
production of the new generation of weapons as soon as the
multilateral convention takes effect.
   Although that gesture is expected to speed work on both the
bilateral and the multilateral treaties, a great deal of work
remains to be done on both, particularly finding the means to make
sure that it is observed, said administration arms control
officials.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Bryan Brumley writes on national security issues
for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
