<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-HebrewBible     12-05 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Hebrew Bible,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Price _ $3 million _ for 1,000-Year-old Hebrew Bible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 1,000-year-old Hebrew Bible sold for a world
record auction price of $3.19 million Tuesday in London, Sotheby's
said.
   Yecheskel Toporowitch, identified only a resident of New York
and Israel, bought the Hebrew Bible, which is believed to have been
written in the Jewish community in Babylon in the 9th or 10th
century.
   Sotheby's said it was the highest price ever paid for a Hebrew
manuscript and the second highest price for any manuscript.
   In 1983, a group of German financiers paid a record $11.7
million for the 12th century Gospels of Henry the Lion.
   The Hebrew Bible was sold by the British Rail Pension Fund,
which bought it for $286,000 in 1978 as an investment at a
Switzerland sale.
   It had come from the library of the late David Solomon Sassoon,
a member of a wealthy Jewish merchant family from Baghdad, who
assembled a world-renown private library of western and oriental
manuscripts.
   The Bible's ownership is known since the 11th century from marks
inside it and is one of five primary works to establish the text of
the Hebrew Bible. It consists of 396 vellum leaves, each inscribed
in dark brown ink, except for the Psalms, which are in two columns.
   The pension fund sold three other Hebrew manuscripts, richly
illuminated with paintings, which also fetched high prices.
   The Rashba Bible, made in Spain and dated 1383, went anonymously
for $1.29 million to become the second-highest price for any Hebrew
manuscript.
   A volume of prayers written in Pesaro, Italy, in 1480 went for
$794,400 to an anonymous buyer who also paid $415,000 for an
incomplete Bible, made in Spain in 1468.
   A Latin prayer book made about 1260 in Amiens, France, and known
as the Du Boisrouvray Psalter, was bought by Paris dealer Pierre
Beres for $1.17 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
