<FIRST>r w AM-Immigration     12-05 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Immigration,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Raising Immigration Quotas Recommended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should increase legal
immigration to fill expected worker shortages and provide 150,000
slots a year for residents now able to the communist nations of
Eastern Europe, a report recommended Tuesday.
   The report by two scholars at the American Enterprise Institute,
a think tank, suggested that more immigrants be ``pre-selected for
specific skills and occupations that are absent or in short supply
in this country.''
   Currently, most immigrants are admitted because they have family
members in the United States, according to authors Ben Wattenberg,
a senior fellow, and Karl Zinsmeister, an adjunct fellow at the
institute. Only 5 percent of immigrant visas now go to those with
an occupational sikll.
   The report said ``many researchers believe that America is
entering an era of long-term labor shortage,'' and concluded that
immigrants would go to regions and occupations where the demand was
greatest.
   Noting that ``thousands of talented persons'' want to leave
Eastern Europe, the report said that it's ``an appropriate moment
to sharply increase our acceptance of East European immigrants.''
   ``We propose a program of `liberty visas _ 150,000 legal slots
per year for 10 years'' for those leaving Eastern Europe, the
report said.
   Such people, the report added, have been ``doubly impeded''
because the United States would not let them in without having
relatives here and the communist states previously would not let
them out.
</TEXT>
