<HEAD>Record Rain in the Northwest, Record Lows and Highs in the South
and the East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered showers fell from Montana to Northern California on
Tuesday. Temperatures hit record lows in five Eastern cities and
record highs in Kansas and Nebraska.
   The showers, which stretched along a cold front and also
extended to northern Nevada, prompted an advisory for up to 6
inches of snow in the mountains and passes of southern and western
Montana.
   The cold front brought a record 2.3 inches of rain to Astoria,
Ore., on Monday, surpassing the 1971 mark for the date by .09 inch.
Kalispell, Mont., got .65 inch, erasing the mark of .18 inch set in
1979.
   Strong winds blew over the northern High Plains on Tuesday.
Morning winds gusted to 60 mph along Interstate 80 west of
Cheyenne, Wyo. A high wind warning was in effect for the mountains
of western Wyoming.
   Low temperatures were in the single digits or below zero across
much of the north Atlantic Coast, and freezing temperatures were
reported as far south as Florida.
   The morning low for the Lower 48 states was 22 degrees below
zero in Saranac, N.Y.
   It was 7 degrees below zero in Concord, N.H., 3 degrees below
the old mark for the date set in 1971. The mercury dropped to a
record 45 degrees in Hollywood, Fla., where the old mark of 46 was
set in 1974. Low-temperature recmton, N.Y. (5, 1971); and Portland, Maine
(7,
1945).
   In contrast, high-temperature records were set in Concordia,
Kan. (69 degrees, 1937) and Lincoln, Neb. (66, 1939).
