<FIRST>r a AM-MissingDoctor     12-05 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Doctor,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Hears From Missing Virginia Doctor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. HOSTETLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Virginia physician who disappeared last
month while in Philadelphia on business has told his family in a
letter that they could write to him at a post office box in Oregon,
police said Tuesday.
   Sgt. Theresa Young said the family of Dr. Todd Arcomano told
police they had received a letter from him on Monday. She said
police were continuing their investigation into his disappearance
to make sure the letter is valid.
   Arcomano, 32, of Arlington, Va., disappeared Nov. 7 after coming
to Philadelphia to take an examination for surgical certification.
He was a general surgeon at Arlington Hospital in suburban
Washington and was locally noted for performing an appendectomy on
Washington Redskins quarterback Doug Williams.
   His brother, Keith Arcomano of Long Branch, N.J., said Tuesday
the letter was sent to their parents, Dr. Nicholas and Ella Cecelia
Arcomano.
   ``Unfortunately, the letter was very vague,'' the brother said.
   It contained no special messages to any family members and did
not indicate when, or if, Arcomano intended to return to Virginia
and his medical practice, he said.
   ``We are satisfied that Todd is safe and not in any harm,'' the
brother said. ``We have been assured that he will contact us again
when he is ready.''
   Lt. Michael Cooney said investigators would try to contact
Arcomano through the post office box in Southbeach, Ore., to verify
his safety.
   Relatives of the Long Branch native said they found Arcomano's
shaving kit, luggage, books and the keys to his 1989 BMW in his
room at the Four Seasons Hotel in Philadelphia. The car was still
parked in the hotel lot.
   An open bottle of cola also was in the room and his books were
open, suggesting he had been studying for his exams. They also
found a handwritten note giving directions to the Amtrak 30th
Street Station.
   Arcomano had reserved the hotel room for only one night. Hotel
employees became suspicious after three days and notified
Arcomano's office.
   Arcomano, a graduate of Georgetown University Medical School,
was due at the family's home in New Jersey the weekend following
his disappearance for a birthday party for his father.
</TEXT>
