<FIRST>r a AM-SavannahStale?     12-05 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Savannah Stale?,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Citizens' Report Blasts City Leadership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scathing report released Tuesday by a
citizens group says 20 years of stale, uninspired city leadership
has made this historic coastal city a ``seemingly underdeveloped
country.''
   The eight-page report titled ``Is Savannah Growing Senile?'' and
prepared by Renaissance Savannah is highly critical of the city's
elected officials, media and business leaders.
   Julie Smith, a Chatham County commissioner and co-chairperson of
the group, said the report was compiled from comments and
observations by members of Renaissance Savannah during the past 12
months.
   The year-old group identifies itself as a grassroots
organization representing all sectors of the city and aimed at
revitalizing Savannah.
   ``What's said here is what I think we've all muttered over beer
and cocktails,'' said Larry Lee, president of the Downtown
Neighborhood Association and a member of Renaissance Savannah.
   The report compares Savannah to a person suffering from
senility, saying both take refuge in the past.
   Of Mayor John Rousakis, who is serving his fifth four-year term,
it says, ``Our city has a mayor who is a ship without a rudder.
   ``Bring him a proposal, he'll say yes or no, or maybe. Then if
he says yes, you owe him. Some cities have mayors who don't wait
for someone to propose a solution _ they bring the parties
together, reconcile the differences and get agreement on making
something happen.''
   Rousakis questioned the validity of the report.
   ``It's obviously a political effort,'' he said. ``The '91 race
(for mayor) is two years away and this is the opening shot.''
   Chatham County Commission Chairman Robert McCorkle accused Ms.
Smith, a Republican, of trying to get black Savannah residents to
support the GOP.
   The report also criticized City Manager Don Mendonsa, saying he
``doesn't realize what an oppressive bureaucracy he has built.''
   ``Honest, hard-working and well respected ... he is one who
manages by control and not by growing creative, independent,
enthusiastic managers,'' it said. ``The result of his 20-plus-year
career in Savannah is an organization that avoids risk and makes
life difficult for many.''
   Mendonsa responded that, to his knowledge, none of the
Renaissance members ``has talked to me about anything.''
   The report said, ``A 20-year period with the same mayor, city
attorney and city manager will be up for grabs during 1991,'' and
added, that then ``The black community may be in a position to
exercise the influence it has long been denied.''
   The report said Savannah has comparatively few residents who
have four years of college and the leadership needs to be more
representative of its blue collar roots.
   Of the Savannah Area Chamber of Commerce, it said, ``The leaders
of the Chamber of Commerce have rarely heard, much less
comprehended, differing opinions within the community.''
   The report challenged journalists and news executives to ``move
their product beyond mediocrity and give attention both to what is
positive about Savannah and to that which would challenge our
elected leaders to better serve our community.''
   Don Harwood, general manager of the Savannah Morning News and
Savannah Evening Press, rejected the report as the opinion of a few
people.
   ``The media are very responsive and responsible in my opinion,''
he said.
</TEXT>
