<FIRST>u i AM-Vogel-Profile 1stLd-Writethru a0741 12-05 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vogel-Profile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0741,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Star Lawyer Arrested, Freed in Communist Cleanup</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs UPDATING that Vogel was released from arrest
with apologies. Picks up 4th graf, Vogel's international .. .</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wolfgang Vogel's spectacular swaps of
American U-2 pilot Gary Powers and major Soviet dissident Natan
Sharansky made him an East German superlawyer during the Cold War,
but his ties to ousted Communist leaders led _briefly _ to his
arrest Tuesday.
   The official East German news agency ADN announced that Vogel
was arrested on suspicion of ``criminal extortion,'' but early
Wednesday ADN said he had been released, that the ``allegation of
criminal extortion had proven to be unfounded'' and that
prosecutors had apologized to him.
   ADN said the allegation concerned Vogel's representation of the
fugitive Alexander Schalck-Golodkowski, but prosecutors had
determined that Vogel ``during his representation of
Schalck-Golodkowski had done his duty as a lawyer, of which
upholding the pledge of secrecy is a part.''
   For three decades, the 64-year old lawyer handled spy swaps,
negotiated the release of political prisoners and helped make sure
the dark doings of East Germany's ousted leaders stayed in the
shadows.
   Once one of only a few dozen private lawyers in all of East
Germany, Vogel for a while was just one of dozens of top Communist
Party officials under fire following reports of massive corruption.
   Vogel's international reputation got its start in 1962 with his
role in arranging the swap of Powers, the American pilot shot down
over Siberia in 1961, for Soviet master spy Rudolf Abel.
   He oversaw the spectacular February 1986 swap _ on a snowy
Glienicke Bridge at the edge of Berlin _ of Soviet human rights
activist Natan Sharansky and three Westerners held on spy charges
in the East for five East Germans convicted of spying in the West.
   Despite his prominent role, Vogel preferred to stay in the
shadows. It was not until 1984 that he gave his first interview to
Western television.
   Inside East Germany, Vogel was a source of hope for thousands of
East Germans imprisoned for political activities who hoped to gain
passage to West by being ``bought'' by the Bonn government.
   For years, East Germany disposed of thousands of its most
troublesome citizes by allowing them to emigrate to West Germany _
for a price that was often negotiated by Vogel.
   As the senior East German official responsible for
``humanitarian affairs'' after the Berlin Wall went up in 1961,
Vogel handled thousands of cases of East German political prisoners
who were able to go West as a result of his intervention.
   Vogel also bailed out the families of top Communist officials to
whom he was so closely linked.
   In 1984, he persuaded the niece of then-Prime Minister Willi
Stoph to return home from the East German Embassy in Prague,
Czechoslovakia, where she was seeking passage to the West. He
persuaded her to apply to leave from East Berlin so as not to
embarrass the party leadership.
   Her passage to West Germany was secured within days of her
return.
   Vogel was born in the Silesian village of Wilhelmsthal, ceded to
Poland after World War II. The son of strict Roman Catholic
parents, he studied law in Jena and Leipzig. He joined the party
only in 1981.
   A veteran of the war, Vogel practiced in the Justice Ministry of
the fledgling Communist state before setting up private practice in
East Berlin in 1954, one of only a few East German lawyers allowed
to do so.
   According to West German newspaper reports, Vogel had at least
one Mercedes-Benz car, went skiing in Austria, and vacationed in
Spain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891205-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 2013EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0747 12-05 1028</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0747,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Plays Down Differences in Bush, Quayle Summit Views</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf17: ``I look,'' with two grafs from as-delivered speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House, dealing with aftershocks from
the Malta summit, attempted to quell criticism from conservatives
Tuesday and play down any differences between President Bush and
Vice President Dan Quayle on the Soviet Union.
   On another summit topic, the administration said the meeting
enabled Bush to look ahead to possible budget savings two years
from now as a result of likely arms reductions.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said that if an
agreement is signed next year to slash long-range nuclear missiles,
``I think that could have an impact, certainly'' on the budget that
would be submitted the following January.
   Bush, on his first day back in the Oval Office, got a standing
ovation from his Cabinet, summoned to the White House for a report
on his two days of talks with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Bush ignored questions from reporters about Quayle, who has
offered a more guarded and skeptical post-summit assessment of the
Soviets than Bush has.
   Quayle, in an interview with The Washington Post, called the
Soviet Union ``a totalitarian government'' and said ``I don't think
they've changed much in foreign policy.''
   Bush, on the other hand, said after the summit, ``We stand at
the threshold of a brand new era of U.S.-Soviet relations.`` He
also said Gorbachev's endorsement of reforms in Eastern Europe
``absolutely mandates new thinking'' by the West.
   Explaining the difference, Bush's national security adviser,
Brent Scowcroft, said, ``We have an administration that is very
closely aligned but I think it probably not possible for people to
speak literally with one voice.''
   ``And there may from time to time be difference of perspective
but there's no difference in the substance of the policies we're
pursuing.''
   For months, Quayle has voiced a harder line than Bush toward the
Soviet Union. It has been suggested the vice president was
deliberately playing to the conservatives as part of a White House
strategy to keep their support.
   But Quayle said Tuesday that ``there's no good guy, bad guy
strategy'' between himself and Bush.
   Quayle, in an interview with Knight-Ridder newspaper editors and
reporters, tempered his comments to the Post, saying he should have
called the Soviet Union an authoritarian, rather than a
totalitarian, state.
   Quayle credited the Soviets with remarkable changes in economic
reforms and their campaign of openness, known as glasnost. ``Where
there has been a lack of `new thinking' on the part of the Soviet
Union is in the area of foreign policy, and particularly in Central
America,'' the vice president said.
   Bush and Quayle talked several times over the summit weekend,
and then discussed the Post interview when they met Tuesday
morning, officials said.
   ``Quayle has stated repeatedly that his No. 1 goal is to be a
loyal, effective vice president to George Bush. If he felt he were
in any way off the reservation, he would get back on,'' said Quayle
spokesman David Beckwith.
   In his first public comment since returning from Malta, Bush
said in remarks prepared for a banquet of the National Republican
Congressional Committee that he made clear to Gorbachev ``America
does not seek to exploit events in Eastern Europe'' but at the same
time was ``up front with President Gorbachev on Central America and
the destabilizing flow of arms into that region from nations
receiving Soviet support. Both of us agreed we don't have to
sacrifice candor to build a better relationship.''
   ``As long as these democratic changes keep moving inside the
Soviet Union and in Eastern Europe, I think the United States ought
to be out there trying to help, not in some kind of superior
manner, but trying to say, `Look. Here's what works,''' Bush told a
crowd of 600 at the $1,000-a-plate GOP dinner, straying extensively
from his prepared text.
   He noted that Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze has
said the Soviets are not looking for a ``bailout'' from the United
States. ``That's good because we don't have any money anyway,''
quipped Bush.
   Some conservatives have expressed unhappiness over the summit,
saying that Bush gave the Soviets economic concessions without
receiving anything in return, such as a commitment to keep
Moscow-made weapons out of Central America.
   Fitzwater minimized those objections. ``I think it's quite
natural to expect that when the president lays out as broad and
comprehensive a set of initiatives as he did there (in Malta), that
there are going to be those who have some concern about them.''
   ``And we certainly will be ready and willing to talk to anybody
about them,'' he said, ``but we don't anticipate huge
difficulties.''
   At the summit, Bush endorsed giving Moscow observer status at
the world's leading economic regulatory body and proposed June as a
target date for completing a trade agreement granting the Soviet
Union most-favored-nation status, which would result in an easing
of trade barriers.
   Fitzwater said the issue of economic cooperation was not linked
to any Soviet concessions.
   Bush, meanwhile, made a telephone call to British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher to offer assurances he wasn't taking sides
against her on the pace of the economic integration of Europe.
   Several major British newspapers had interpreted Bush's remarks
at a briefing Monday for NATO leaders as a rebuff that had isolated
Mrs. Thatcher from Britain's 11 partners in the European Economic
Community.
   Bush had told the allies that the reforms in Eastern Europe
required a ``continued, perhaps even intensified, effort of the 12
to integrate'' and become a magnet for the reform process.
   Scowcroft said Bush called Mrs. Thatcher ``to clarify some of
the items that were in the British press.'' Saying there was no
change in U.S. policy, Scowcroft said the administration supports
economic integration but that ``the details of it and the pace of
it (are) up to the Europeans, not the United States.''
   Mrs. Thatcher faces a lone battle at a summit this weekend of
the 12-nation European Economic Community against French-led plans
for monetary integration and community-wide rules on labor unions
and employment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891205-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 2107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SecretTaxFiles     12-05 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Secret Tax Files,0802</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tax Rights Advocates: Court Ruling Could Open Files</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court ruling was hailed
Tuesday as the wedge that could pry open the Internal Revenue
Service's files on taxpayers the agency takes to court.
   However, a spokeswoman for the IRS in Washington said the files
are already available to taxpayers upon request.
   ``This is a major decision, a major civil rights decision. The
appeals court has granted the taxpayer the right to know what the
secret files contain and to use the information in his own
defense,'' said Paul DesFosses of the National Coalition of IRS
Whistleblowers.
   In a telephone interview from his Pocatello, Idaho, office,
DesFosses said the coalition is a watchdog group of current and
former IRS employees.
   ``There's no telling how many innocent taxpayers have been
convicted of crimes in the past that they were innocent of,'' he
said.
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans last week
ordered the IRS to open its files in a Dallas case of a father and
son accused of helping to prepare false tax returns and conspiring
to defraud the federal government.
   Stephen M. Buford, 36, now of Chicago, was convicted on all
counts. His father, Bob A. Buford, 61, of Dallas, was convicted of
conspiracy. They filed an appeal in 1988.
   The 5th Circuit also ordered a new trial for the Bufords, saying
the judge in the case gave erroneous instructions to the jury.
   The two men referred questions to their attorney, Michael Minns
of Houston.
   ``It's a major breakthrough,'' Minns said. ``It means a lot of
things to the individual taxpayer. If you want these confidential
records, you're entitled to them. If you're accused of something,
you have a right to these records.''
   The IRS authorized what are known as individual master files on
each taxpayer in 1984 as part of a five-year plan, said DesFosses,
who testified on behalf of the Bufords. The IRS files are kept in a
computer in West Virginia, he said.
   ``Unless you're familiar with it, it's something right out of
George Orwell,'' he said.
   The computer ``has everything you can possibly imagine in it
under your Social Security number,'' Minns said.
   The 5th Circuit opinion said each IRS file ``includes,
primarily, a breakdown of all information relevant to the tax
status of the individual,'' such as tax and refund payments, filing
status and number of children.
   DesFosses said the files also contain information on any
taxpayer activity that involves a government agency, such as
selling property or obtaining a building permit.
   In the Dallas trial, prosecutors claimed that Stephen Buford had
not filed his personal tax returns from 1980 to 1984, Minns said.
   Buford said he had filed, and he asked the IRS to let him see
his individual master file to prove it.
   The IRS refused to provide the file, portions of which are in
code, and instead provided handwritten notes it said summarized the
file.
   The U.S. District judge hearing the case ordered the IRS to let
him see the file to determine if Buford could use it in his
defense. However, the judge never looked at the file, according to
the opinion.
   On Nov. 29, the 5th Circuit ordered the judge to look at
Buford's file.
   ``If this reveals that Stephen actually did not file his
personal tax returns in the years 1980 through 1984, no harm was
done. If, on the other hand, it turns out that Stephen did file, as
he says, then he must be granted the use of that evidence at the
new trial which we direct,'' the 5th Circuit said.
   Although IRS records are open, DesFosses said the agency doesn't
open files to people who are charged with tax crimes. He claimed
the IRS has wrongly prosecuted taxpayers based on ``fraudulently
prepared handwritten assessments, not the original documents.''
   The appeals court ruling is significant because it means ``the
IRS may no longer use handwritten or secondary records. They are
going to have to use original records,'' DesFosses said.
   Ellen Murphy, public relations director for the IRS, said the
agency keeps tax information for 200 million accounts on its master
files and does not gather information surreptitiously on taxpayers.
   ``It does have confidential information in it. Your tax matters
are not subject to disclosure. But you can call or write and ask
for it. It's free,'' she said.
   The files are coded to reduce the amount of computer space the
records use, she said. Taxpayers can see the files under the
Freedom of Information Act and the privacy act, she said.
