<FIRST>r a AM-JusticeDenied     12-05 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Justice Denied,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advocate of Wrongfully Convicted Arrested on Drug Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE MITTELSTADT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Justice Denied, an advocacy group for
the wrongfully convicted, is being held on federal drug and
conspiracy charges after an FBI agent recognized his photograph
from a fund-raiser, authorities said Tuesday.
   A professor who studies crime and supported Justice Denied
questioned the FBI's timing and motivation in arresting the group's
president, private investigator Jim Humphreys.
   Humphreys, 40, was being held in Dallas' Lew Sterrett Justice
Center on 10 counts each of possession of cocaine and intent to
distribute cocaine, and one count of conspiracy, a jailer at the
center said.
   He was arrested Monday after an FBI agent noticed a newspaper
story about a Saturday fund-raiser for the newly formed Justice
Denied.
   The group is supported by Randall Dale Adams, who was freed from
prison after his murder conviction was examined in the film ``The
Thin Blue Line,'' and Lenell Geter, an engineer whose robbery
conviction was overturned in 1984 with Humphreys' help.
   ``We happened to see the story but we knew he (Humphreys) was
probably in this area,'' FBI spokesman Woody Specht said.
   The charges, filed Nov. 15, stem from 10 incidents during which
Humphreys allegedly sold between one gram and eight ounces of
cocaine in Oklahoma City in 1985. The charges are part of a
57-count indictment returned by an Oklahoma City grand jury last
month, Specht said.
   Oklahoma City FBI spokesman Dan Vogel said the indictment was
sealed and details could not be released.
   Humphreys' bond was set at $25,000 by Magistrate William F.
Sanders, Specht said.
   Ronald Huff, a professor of public policy and management at Ohio
State University, said Humphreys' arrest may represent a backlash
against the efforts of Justice Denied. Huff, who recently completed
a five-year study on wrongful convictions, attended the fund-raiser.
   ``There is some concern about vindictiveness in Dallas,'' Huff
said in a telephone interview. ``Jim Humphreys has played a key
role in helping prove the innocence of some of these people which
has caused him to be persona non grata.''
   Huff said the timing of the arrest just two days after the
fund-raiser was ``very curious.''
   ``It seems illogical to me why a fellow would put himself on TV
and allow a lot of photographs if he's wanted. It seems suspicious
to me on the surface,'' he said.
   Specht was not immediately available to respond to Huff's
comments, and other FBI officials referred all questions to Specht.
   Humphreys' investigative work helped clear Geter, an engineer
who spent 16 months in a Texas prison for a robbery before another
suspect was identified. Geter is chairman of Justice Denied's
advisory board.
   There was no answer Tuesday at Geter's home in Columbia, S.C.
   Also attending the fund-raiser was Adams, who spent 12 years
behind bars for the 1976 shooting death of a Dallas patrolman.
``The Thin Blue Line'' questioned the testimony of prosecution
witnesses in the case. A state appeals court later overturned the
conviction and authorities chose not to seek a retrial.
   Calls to the Justice Denied office weren't answered Tuesday.
   Edith Neely Crosley, treasurer of Justice Denied, told the
Dallas Times Herald she had not heard about Humphreys' arrest, but
felt it would not hurt the organization.
   ``There are too many people involved with it and they are too
dedicated to it. We will continue on,'' she said.
</TEXT>
