<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru a0766 12-05 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0766,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Woman Charged With Terrorism, Faces 20 Years in Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS three grafs at end with further fighting. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SAL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Connecticut woman in whose
back yard police found ammunition and explosives buried was charged
with terrorism late Tuesday by Salvadoran authorities.
   Jennifer Casolo, 28, spent more than four hours behind closed
doors making a sworn deposition to military Judge Guillermo Romero.
   ``I'm being taken to the women's prison. It's a place I've taken
many delegations, a place where I've interviewed many prisoners. I
guess now I'll be on the other side,'' she told reporters when she
emerged from the judge's chambers.
   The judge avoided contact with reporters waiting at the court,
but Ms. Casolo and her lawyer, Salvador Ibarra, both said she had
been charged under the terrorism law with possession of weapons of
war.
   She faces up to 20 years in prison if convicted.
   Ms. Casolo, a native of Thomaston, Conn., and a former Seattle
resident, has spent nearly five years here as the representative of
Christian Educational Seminars, a San Antonio-based organization
that arranges fact-finding tours for visiting Americans, including
congressmen.
   Her house was raided Nov. 25 by police who found more than
20,000 rounds of assault rifle ammunition, explosives and detonator
caps buried in her back yard.
   She has denied complicity with the leftist Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front, which is waging a 10-year-old war
against a succession of U.S.-backed governments. She has said she
rented the house where the munitions were found only three months
ago, and that she has been traveling much of that time.
   ``I have faith in all the people who have written me letters, in
their prayers. I can't say I have faith in the system to find me
innocent. But I believe my innocence will shine through,'' she said
before being driven off to prison.
   She had spent the previous 10 days under arrest at National
Police headquarters.
   Ms. Casolo was arrested in the middle of a major offensive the
guerrillas launched Nov. 11. The capital and countryside have been
relatively quiet in recent days, but the insurgents say the push,
which has claimed the lives of well over 1,000 rebels, soldiers and
civilians, will continue.
   Former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark traveled to El
Salvador to assist in Ms. Casolo's defense. He said before leaving
for the United States late Tuesday that he thought her prospects
for acquittal were good.
   ``The accusations against me are false,'' said Ms. Casolo.
``This is a first step and the rest will be decided by the long
judicial process here.''
   Clark said he would return to help with future phases of the
trial. He had said shortly after arrival late last week that
deportation was probably Ms. Casolo's best bet.
   But she told reporters Tuesday: ``Let us prove our innocence
publicly. We're not going to go behind the scenes.''
   Guerrillas meanwhile took over two small neighborhoods on the
western side of the city before dawn Tuesday, held them for several
hours and then left, the armed forces said. The military press
office said one soldier was killed and five were wounded in the
fighting.
   ``Soldiers came in after the guerrillas went back to the
volcano,'' a resident of Escalon North said.
   A dusk-to-dawn curfew that has been reduced to 11 p.m. to 5 a.m.
in the capital remains in effect in Zacatecoluca, 25 miles
southeast of San Salvador, because of persistent fighting, the
armed forces said.
</TEXT>
