<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 2130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan     12-05 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arms Control Elsewhere Won't Affect Japan's Military Growth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   TOKY0 (AP) _ U.S.-Soviet arms-control agreements will not stop
the upgrading of Japan's military capability, Foreign Ministry
spokesman Taizo Watanabe said Tuesday.
   Watanabe said in reply to a question by foreign journalists that
Japan strongly supports progress toward arms reduction.
   He said Japan has been criticized for insufficiencies in its own
defense and that the military buildup that has been under way for
years ``is for the purpose of securing our self-defense.''
   ``It is separate from arms reductions from that point of view.
So our own efforts for improving our self-defense are not expected
to change at the moment.''
   Newspaper reports here said last week that Japan's next defense
budget will show a routine 6 percent growth.
   Watanabe had been asked whether arms-control developments
signaled at the U.S.-Soviet summit in Malta would affect Japan's
defense program.
   His reply demonstrated Japan's removal from rapidly improving
big-power relations in Europe and the different strategic situation
in the Far East.
   The Japanese taxpayer seems unlikely to get any early benefit
from an end of the Cold War. Washington is talking about
substantial cuts in military budgets, and U.S. Secretary of Defense
Dick Cheney said recently evidence exists that the Soviets have
reduced military spending.
   Japan, however, is looking for steady growth. The Asahi Shimbun
and other newspapers reported last week that the Finance Ministry
had agreed on an increase of just under 6 percent in the defense
budget for the fiscal year starting next April.
   Japan's constitution, imposed by U.S. occupation authorities
after World War II, disavows war and the use of military force.
   Japan depends for its defense on both its own military forces
and U.S. forces obligated by treaty to help Japan, Watanabe noted.
   ``We are very much concerned about this question of the position
of the United States on naval forces,'' he added.
   When President Bush said he and Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev disagreed at Malta about reductions in naval forces, he
had in mind the vast Pacific.
   Under Gorbachev, the Soviet Union has suggested that Japan talk
about Soviet-Japanese military issues. Japan has refused, always
citing its obligation to the United States under the defense
treaty. The United States also rejects talking about naval
reductions in the Pacific.
   Japan's defense budget will be about $27.8 billion, roughly 1
percent of gross national product, Asahi said. The U.S. defense
budget is more than 10 times as large. The United States devotes
about 6 percent of its gross national product to defense.
   Japan has cool relations with Moscow and demands that the
Soviets return a group of islands off northern Japan that Soviet
troops took in the last days of World War II. The dispute is the
main issue blocking agreement on a peace treaty between the two
countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
