<SECOND>AM-Transplant, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0772,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Improving Following Multiple Organ Transplant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `Meanwhile, the ..., and 12th graf, `Mrs. Smith
..., to RESTORE donor appearing at Chicago hospital.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's first recipient of a transplanted
heart, kidney and liver was upgraded from critical to serious
condition Tuesday and talked with her husband after her respirator
was removed, a hospital spokesman said.
   Cindy Martin, 26, of the eastern Pennsylvania town of Archbald,
was ``doing very well'' two days after the 21{ hour operation that
began Saturday night, said Frank Raczkiewicz, spokesman at
Presbyterian-University Hospital.
   ``Her organs look excellent,'' said Dr. John Armitage, who
performed the transplant.
   Raczkiewicz said Mrs. Martin spoke with her husband, John, after
she was removed from a respirator. Nurses said she was in good
spirits.
   The operation marked the first time doctors simultaneously
transplanted a liver, heart and kidney in a patient.
   Mrs. Martin is receiving a new Japanese anti-rejection drug,
FK-506, which is believed to be more effective than the traditional
anti-rejection drug, cyclosporine.
   Mrs. Martin suffers from familial cardiomyopathy, an inherited
heart disease. She received a heart transplant three years ago, but
her body rejected the heart, she developed hepatitis and her
kidneys failed.
   In Chicago, meanwhile, the nation's first living liver donor
said she felt ``real good'' a week after the operation.
   Teresa Smith, 29, sat in a wheelchair at her first public
appearance since she and her daughter, Alyssa, underwent the dual
operations Nov. 27.
   Mrs. Smith said she had seen her 21-month-old daughter several
times since the weekend. ``She usually wants me to hold her, which
I can't at this point,'' she said.
   Although the operations drew lots of attention, ``I don't feel
like a `first,''' she said. ``I feel like any parent who is looking
out for the best interests of her child.''
   Mrs. Smith will be discharged before the weekend, said Dr. Peter
Whitington, director of pediatric services at University of Chicago
Hospitals. And there is a 50 percent chance Alyssa will be released
in time to spend Christmas at home, he said.
   She remained in serious but stable condition. Her liver suffered
minor damage in a second operation to stop bleeding, but there are
no signs of rejection, Whitington said.
   Alyssa suffers from biliary atresia, an often-fatal congenital
disorder that is the leading cause of liver transplants involving
children.
</TEXT>
