<HEAD>Administration Concered over Trapped Americans in Manila</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOPS with 6 grafs; all hotels believed evacuated; picks up 7th
graf 1st Ld: ``Before the,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Embassy officials in Manila met a ``great
number'' of Americans on buses carrying trapped civilians to safety
from besieged downtown hotels, a State Department spokeswoman said
Tuesday night.
   ``We've heard that all the hotels have been evacuated,'' said
the spokeswoman, Mary Yates.
   She said the department was not sure what would happen next, but
``It just continues to be good news'' from Manila.
   Consular officers met the 30 buses being used in pairs on the
hotel shuttle at a reception center established at a shopping
center near the airport. ``They've seen a great number of
Americans,'' Yates said.
   But she said, ``We're not going to be able to get into numbers
for some time'' of how many Americans were evacuated.
   An estimated 215 Americans were among some 2,000 foreigners
trapped for four days in hotels by the military rebellion that had
killed at least 77 people.
   Before the government of Cory Aquino and the rebels established
a cease-fire to permit evacuation of the hotels, the Bush
administration had urged restraint on both sides.
   President Bush, who ordered U.S. jets to fly over rebel bases to
prevent their use on the first day of the coup attempt, was said to
be keeping options open. National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft
said that Aquino thus far had not requested additional U.S.
military support.
   There had been reports from Manila that insurgents seeking to
oust Aquino, unhappy over U.S. support for her government, might
not release trapped Americans.
   But a statement issued Wednesday said the insurgents' executive
committee decided late Tuesday to free all the Americans because
``these American tourists are not our enemy.''
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said there was ``no
indication'' that any of the Americans ``have been the targets of
attack.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater and other U.S. officials
sought to minimize the remaining threat left to Aquino, suggesting
she now clearly has the upper hand in the struggle. ``It's been a
gradual reassertion of control by the government,'' Fitzwater said.
   In Honolulu, Air Force Lt. Col. Tom Boyd, spokesman for the U.S.
Pacific Command, said there were no U.S. troop movements or plans
to deploy special units from Hawaii to deal with the situation in
Manila.
   Even at U.S. bases in the Philippines, military officials are
merely ``monitoring the situation,'' not setting up for more U.S.
involvement, he said. U.S. troops and their dependents in the
Philippines are under minimum travel restrictions, which means they
may travel to and from the bases and their homes off-base, but not
much else, Boyd said.
</TEXT>
