</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was subjected as a child to Josef
Mengele's notorious experiments on twins said the Nazi medical data
gathered from her suffering should never be used in scientific
research.
   Eva Mozes Kor told her story Monday at a Boston University
conference on Nazi doctors and parallels in modern medicine. Some
in the audience of about 300 people wept and when she finished many
stood and cheered her.
   ``No one should benefit from brutal crimes,'' said Kor, a
Hungarian Jew and president of CANDLES, which stands for Children
of Auschwitz Nazi Deadly Lab Experiments.
   Some biomedical ethicists contend that the issue is moot,
because Nazi research already has been cited in American and
British journals. They argue that the data, despite its source,
have the potential to save human life.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy learned a lesson when
Greenpeace anti-nuclear protesters halted the submarine launch of a
Trident 2 missile in July, and it was ready for them this time.
   In a high seas drama 50 miles off the Florida coast on Monday,
Navy ships rammed and fire-hosed the 190-foot MV Greenpeace vessel
while helicopters buzzed two small high-speed rafts. Sailors in
motorized rafts cut the fuel lines of one Greenpeace raft before
towing both out of the launch safety zone.
   With their vessels helpless, about 25 Greenpeace activists could
only watch as the nuclear submarine Tennessee unleashed the Trident
2, the Navy's newest, most powerful weapon, on a successful test
launch.
   The 44-foot missile shot out of a tube in the sub's deck, broke
the sea's surface, ignited and hurled a dummy warhead package to an
ocean target several thousand miles away.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is scrambling to
replace M. Danny Wall, who is resigning as the nation's top savings
and loan regulator after 2{ years of bitter struggle with Congress.
   Wall, characterizing his job as a ``thankless and perhaps
impossible task,'' resigned in a letter to President Bush on
Monday. He said he was leaving to spare his Office of Thrift
Supervision the disruption that would be caused by continuing his
fight for political survival.
   Until Thanksgiving, the House Banking Committee was holding
weekly hearings spotlighting Wall's failure to contain what could
become the nation's largest S&amp;L failure. The regulator was spending
much of his time responding to his critics.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady praised Wall for his
``public spirited'' decision to resign and said the department had
began the search for his successor.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is conducting a
preliminary inquiry on whether a special prosecutor should
investigate allegations that former Housing Secretary Samuel R.
Pierce violated the law.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh disclosed late Monday that he
had ordered the preliminary inquiry into allegations submitted last
month by 19 Democrats on the House Judiciary Committee.
   The department has 60 days to complete the preliminary inquiry.
Thornburgh's chief spokesman David Runkel said it began Saturday.
   Under the law, the inquiry by the Justice Department's public
integrity section must determine if there are ``reasonable grounds
to believe that further investigation is warranted'' by special
prosecutor, known as an independent counsel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
