<FIRST>a a BC-History Adv10   12-05 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-History, Adv10,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING b0771 of Dec. 4 to fix to advance priority</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, Dec. 10, the 344th day of 1989. There are 21
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Twenty-five years ago, on Dec. 10, 1964, civil rights activist
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. received the Nobel Peace Prize during
ceremonies in Oslo, Norway.
   On this date:
   In 1520, Martin Luther publicly burned the papal edict demanding
that he recant, or face excommunication.
   In 1817, Mississippi was admitted to the Union as the 20th state.
   In 1830, poet Emily Dickinson was born in Amherst, Mass.
   In 1869, women were granted the right to vote in the Wyoming
Territory.
   In 1898, a treaty was signed in Paris officially ending the
Spanish-American War.
   In 1906, President Theodore Roosevelt became the first American
to be awarded the Nobel Peace Prize, for helping to mediate an end
to the Russo-Japanese War.
   In 1931, Jane Addams was named a co-recipient of the Nobel Peace
Prize, the first American woman so honored.
   In 1948, the United Nations General Assembly adopted its
Universal Declaration on Human Rights.
   In 1950, Ralph J. Bunche was presented the Nobel Peace Prize,
the first black American to receive the award.
   In 1958, the first domestic passenger jet flight took place in
the United States as a National Airlines Boeing 707 flew 111
passengers from New York to Miami in about 2{ hours.
   In 1967, singer Otis Redding died in the crash of his private
plane in Wisconsin. He was 26.
   In 1983, Raul Alfonsin was inaugurated after nearly eight years
of military rule in Argentina.
   Ten years ago: NBC-TV interviewed one of the American hostages
in Iran, Marine Corp. William Gallegos, after agreeing to several
conditions set by the captors, including the airing of an unedited
statement by an Iranian militant.
   Five years ago: South African Bishop Desmond Tutu received the
Nobel Peace Prize.
   One year ago: Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev visited the
republic of Armenia, the scene of a devastating earthquake that
killed an estimated 25,000 people.
   Today's Birthdays: Composer-conductor Morton Gould, president of
ASCAP, is 76. Actress Dorothy Lamour is 75. Actor Harold Gould is
66. Secretary of Agriculture Clayton Yeutter is 59. Actress Susan
Dey is 37.
   Thought for Today: ``There are many persons who look on Sunday
as a sponge to wipe out the sin of the week.'' _ Henry Ward
Beecher, American clergyman and social reformer (1813-1887).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Use Sunday, December 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891205-0179 </DOCNO>
