<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     12-05 0849</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0890</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   M. Danny Wall, under fire for his handling of
the costliest savings and loan failure in history, has resigned as
the government's chief S&amp;L regulator.
   In his letter of resignation to President Bush on Monday, Wall
said he was being made ``a scapegoat'' for the problems of the
entire industry. He also complained of a ``steady stream of
one-sided information'' from congressional hearings concerning the
collapse of the Lincoln Savings and Loan Association of Irvine,
Calif.
   He specifically criticized Rep. Henry Gonzalez, D-Texas,
chairman of the House Banking Committee, saying Gonzalez ``resorted
to corruption of the truth'' in trying to force him out.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. has spent an ``unbelievable'' $1.9
billion cleaning up last spring's Alaskan oil spill, Transportation
Secretary Samuel Skinner said.
   It was the highest detailed estimate of the cleanup cost for the
March spill yet given by either the government or the company.
   Skinner, continuing his long-running praise of Exxon's efforts,
said Monday the full story of the extent of the cleanup after the
tanker Exxon Valdez ran aground in Prince William Sound has not
been told. The ship spilled more than 10 million gallons of Alaskan
crude oil that spread over a vast area.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LIN Broadcasting Corp. said its board has
recommended to its shareholders a revised $3.38 billion offer from
McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. for controlling interest in LIN.
   The New York-based cellular telephone, broadcasting and
publishing concern took the action Monday after resisting McCaw's
overtures since September, when it reached an agreement with
BellSouth Corp. on combining cellular interests.
   LIN said it was asking BellSouth to terminate their agreement on
combining cellular operations, but spokeswoman Carlton Horton in
Atlanta said BellSouth was studying the request and did not expect
to have any immediate comment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories dropped 0.2 percent
in October, the second straight monthly decline, the government
said in its latest report on the sluggishness gripping American
industry.
   The Commerce Department said Monday orders for both durable and
non-durable manufactured goods fell to a seasonally adjusted $233.9
billion following a revised 1 percent decline in September.
September originally was reported to be unchanged following a 2.8
percent increase in August.
   The level of orders was the lowest since $230.4 billion were
written last July.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of new homes fell 0.5 percent in
October, the government said. Analysts said overall purchases were
driven down by a 24.7 percent decline in the West due to the San
Francisco Bay-area earthquake and the effects of the slowing
economy.
   The Commerce Department said Monday that new single-family homes
were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 649,000 in
October following a revised 10.2 percent plunge in September.
September sales originally were reported down 14 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court said it will decide whether
the federal government's delays in setting clean-air guidelines
limit its power to fine polluters.
   The justices said Monday they will hear an appeal by General
Motors Corp., which faces fines of up to $25,000 a day for
violating air-quality standards at a Massachusetts car-assembly
plant.
   In another business-related case, the court agreed to decide
whether U.S. banks with branch offices overseas must pay depositors
after foreign governments seize or freeze those accounts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $16 million personal backruptcy plan for
former Ohio financier Marvin L. Warner has won court approval after
two years of wrangling, but the government may appeal.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge George Proctor said Monday the Internal
Revenue Service would get about $13 million it is owed in yearly
installments. The government argued that the Warner assets could be
dissipated before the IRS gets paid.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Corp. has recalled all 8,000 luxury
Lexus LS400 automobiles to fix a sticky cruise control mechanism
and replace a stoplight cover.
   It is the first recall of the cars, which dealers officially
began selling in early September. Toyota also makes the Lexus
ES250, which is unaffected by the recall.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency is calling
for curbs on the pesticide EBDC, saying widespread use of the
chemical on scores of crops from apples to tomatoes poses an
unreasonable cancer risk.
   The EPA on Monday proposed eliminating the use of the EBDC
family of fungicides on 45 crops, but said its continued use on
another 10 food products, including grapes, onions and cranberries,
``do not present an unreasonable risk'' to consumers.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rose slightly Monday. The Dow Jones average of
30 industrials advanced 5.98 points to 2,753.63, its ninth-highest
close ever.
   The dollar finished mixed against major foreign currencies.
   Bond prices were narrowly mixed in quiet trading.
   Gold prices tumbled more than $12 an ounce as investors reacted
to a recent run-up in prices and large supplies.
   On other markets, cotton was off sharply, grain and soybean
futures were lower, cattle futures were mostly higher and pork
futures dropped, and energy futures were mostly higher.
