<FIRST>r f PM-SteelImporters     12-05 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel Importers,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steel Importers Call for Change in Anti-Dumping Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel importers say fair-trade laws are being
abused to protect U.S. steel companies from foreign competition and
urged an international trading body to examine the issue.
   The importers pinned their criticism Monday on anti-dumping
laws, which are intended to prevent foreign companies from selling
in the United States at unfairly low prices.
   Foreign producers can run afoul of anti-dumping laws through no
fault of their own, simply because of a drop in the value of the
dollar, the American Institute for Imported Steel said at a New
York news conference.
   A consultant for the trade group said in an interview that
Commerce Department officials had admitted to him that they
selectively prosecuted foreign companies under anti-dumping laws as
a warning to others.
   ``They were actually proud of using the laws somewhat unevenly _
just to keep the foreign producers on their toes,'' said Hans
Mueller, an economics professor at Middle Tennessee State
University.
   A Commerce Department spokeswoman said she could not immediately
comment on the professor's statement.
   The trade group said U.S. anti-dumping laws should be reviewed
by the current Uruguay Round of the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade, a multinational set of free-trade talks.
   The steel importers said they were pleased with the Bush
administration's commitment to free-trade principles and hoped it
would back the drive for changes in anti-dumping laws.
   The Bush administration lobbied against heavy restraints on
imported steel and succeeded in holding the renewal this fall to 2{
years, instead of five as U.S. steel makers had requested. Foreign
countries that eliminate subsidies will be given raises in their
quotas.
   In addition to importing steel, members of the trade group also
export some American-made steel. The institute said it supports the
Bush administration's commitment to worldwide elimination of
subsidies, reduction of tariffs and elimination of non-tariff
barriers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
