<DOCNO> AP891205-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryBills     12-05 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rates Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities fell in Monday's auction.
   The Treasury Department sold $8 billion in three-month bills at
an average discount rate of 7.55 percent, down from 7.63 percent
last week. Another $8 billion was sold in six-month bills at an
average discount rate of 7.30 percent, down from 7.45 percent last
week.
   The rates were the lowest since three-month bills sold for 7.52
percent last Oct. 23, and six-month bills averaged 7.26 percent on
Aug. 8, 1988.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.80 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,809.20 and 7.69 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,630.90.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 7.73
percent last week, up from 7.64 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
