<DOCNO> AP891205-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 0158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-US-SovietBusiness     12-05 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet Business,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Companies Urged To Act Quickly To Exploit Perestroika</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American companies must move quickly to take
advantage of the opportunities offered by Soviet perestroika during
the coming years or fall further behind foreign competitors, says
the chairman of Pepsico Inc.
   ``If you want to go you better get there now, because if you
wait someone else will have the business,'' Don Kendall told
American executives attending a U.S.-Soviet business symposium
Monday.
   Kendall was one of several American and Soviet speakers at the
symposium produced by Business Week magazine, called ``The Opening
of the Soviet Market: Implications for Global Business.''
   Dennis Sokol, chairman of Medical Services Partners Inc. and
president of a Soviet-American medical consortium, said that of the
approximately 1,000 joint ventures created in the past year between
Soviet and foreign companies, fewer than 100 involve American
companies.
   Kendall, whose soft-drink company in 1972 produced the first
American consumer product sold in the Soviet Union, said that even
in the era of perestroika _ the political and economic
restructuring proposed by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev _
there are big obstacles for U.S. businesses.
   Among them are the difficulty of doing business in a
cash-starved nation where profits cannot easily be taken out of the
country. Full convertibility of the ruble, the main hindrance to
U.S. companies doing business in the Soviet Union, could take
longer than a decade, Kendall said.
   ``You need to start by acknowledging that Soviet change will
take time, lots of time,'' he said.
   Conference participants learned first-hand of the problems faced
in conducting business between the two nations _ members of a
Soviet delegation did not attend because visas were not issued on
time.
   Kendall praised the weekend summit in Malta between President
Bush and Gorbachev as a step toward helping perestroika succeed,
but urged the United States to loosen trade restrictions that now
hinder U.S.-Soviet commerce.
   He also called for most favored nation status for the Soviet
Union, which would lower tariffs on U.S. imports from the Soviets,
and for dropping conditions for granting the Soviets observer
status at the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   Sokol said the most serious problem facing U.S. companies in
entering the Soviet Union was the lack of hard currency.
   Nevertheless, joint venture opportunities abound in many areas
such as the medical supply field, where acute shortages exist, he
said. Soviet medical supply companies currently are able to meet
only 65 percent of demand, Sokol said.
   Soviet officials who did attend the symposium outlined a series
of problems facing their nation as it carries out perestroika,
including massive economic reforms.
   Vladamir Checklin, head of the Soviet Trade and Economic
Council, compared the current struggle between the old centralized
economic system and the emerging reforms with that of a patient
undergoing psychiatric treatment.
   ``As the therapy starts it brings out a lot of serious
diseases,'' he said. The first step to perestroika, Checklin said,
is that ``It's our problem. We have to do it ourselves.''
   Among the changes needed for the Soviets to compete in the
global economy, he said, is a reorientation of the manufacturing
sector.
   ``We haven't manufactured in the Soviet Union for Western
markets,'' he said. ``We need to change in order to compete.''
   Checklin also said a number of proposals would be taken up by
the new Soviet congress to further the reforms, including revising
tax policies and privatization of unprofitable businesses.
   ``The proof of the pudding is in the eating and many more U.S.
companies are liking this pudding,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
