<DOCNO> AP891205-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 0200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-LIN-McCaw Bjt   12-05 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LIN-McCaw, Bjt,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>LIN Board Recommends Accepting Revised McCaw Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After resisting earlier bids, LIN Broadcasting
Corp.'s board is recommending to its shareholders a revised $3.38
billion offer from McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. for
controlling interest in LIN.
   At the same time, LIN said Monday it had asked BellSouth Corp.
to terminate its agreement with LIN on combining the cellular phone
operations of the two companies.
   Spokeswoman Carlton Horton in Atlanta said BellSouth was
studying the request but did not expect to have any immediate
comment on it.
   Geoffrey Johnson, who follows the telecommunications industry
for Argus Research Corp., said BellSouth could come back with a
revision of its offer.
   ``This doesn't mean the BellSouth deal is dead,'' he said. ``I
would be fairly amazed if BellSouth walks away from this.''
   LIN, a New York-based cellular telephone, broadcasting and
publishing concern, had resisted McCaw's overtures since September,
when LIN reached an agreement with BellSouth on combining their
cellular interests.
   But LIN said Monday that McCaw submitted a revised buyout offer
Friday and the two sides ``conducted negotiations'' on it over the
weekend.
   LIN said BellSouth was invited to revise their cellular merger
agreement, but said the regional telephone company ``has not done
so at this time.''
   It said it could not enter a binding agreement with McCaw as
long as the merger agreement with BellSouth remains in effect.
   The Kirkland, Wash.-based McCaw is the largest U.S. cellular
telephone company, with nearly 50 million potential customers, but
it is seeking access to bigger markets in an effort to create a
national cellular network.
   The combined LIN and BellSouth cellular interests would have had
about 55 million potential customers, while a McCaw-LIN company
would have 70 million, including customers in five of the top 10
markets.
   ``Throughout this long process, our goal has has been to
maximize stockholder value,'' Donald A. Pels, LIN's president and
chief executive, said in a statement. ``The board's action in
recommending the revised McCaw offer is in accordance with that
goal.''
   The board's recommendation was announced after the stock market
closed.
   In national over-the-counter trading, LIN rose $1.50 a share to
close at $121.62{ while McCaw gained 75 cents a share to $39.25.
BellSouth rose 37{ cents a share to $54 in trading on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Under the new proposal, McCaw offered to buy 21.9 million shares
of LIN at $154.11 per share. With the 5.1 million LIN shares that
McCaw now owns, that would give McCaw just over 50 percent of LIN's
53.9 million common shares.
   Previously, McCaw offered to buy 22.5 million shares of LIN at
$150 per share.
   While each cash offer was worth $3.38 billion, McCaw said in the
revised proposal it would give LIN its nearly 5 percent interest in
a Los Angeles cellular franchise after the tender offer.
   As in the earlier offer, McCaw also would have LIN buy $425
million of McCaw stock and distribute it to LIN stockholders other
than McCaw.
   Under its agreement with BellSouth, LIN shareholders would get a
cash dividend of $42 a share, a 50 percent stake in the new
cellular company and stock in a new company that would consist of
LIN's seven television stations.
   Argus' Johnson said he estimated the value of the McCaw offer at
about $131 a share, up from $127.50 a share under its previous
offer due to inclusion of the Los Angeles cellular interest. He
valued the BellSouth offer at $124 a share.
   The terms of their agreement to merge cellular operations would
give BellSouth $54 million plus expenses if the agreement is
terminated.
   LIN had turned to BellSouth in September, coming up with the
plan to merge cellular interests after talks with McCaw broke down.
McCaw began its pursuit of LIN in early June.
   In Monday's announcement, LIN noted that as long as the
BellSouth merger agreement continues in effect, it cannot enter
into a binding agreement covering the new McCaw proposal.
   It added, however, that McCaw is ``irrevocably committed'' until
Feb. 28, 1990, to enter into a binding agreement with LIN as long
as LIN's board continues to recommend the McCaw transaction.
   If BellSouth does not terminate the merger agreement, LIN could
do so if LIN shareholders fail to approve it at a Jan 12
stockholders meeting called to consider the BellSouth deal.
</TEXT>
