<DOCNO> AP891205-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 0135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-SovietEconomy Bjt   12-05 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Economy, Bjt,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economic Initiatives Symbolic for Soviets: Analysts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economic incentives President Bush
proposed in Malta will allow Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
to claim an important symbolic victory, but they will do little to
help Gorbachev rescue his ailing economy, say U.S. experts on the
Soviet Union.
   Those analysts said they viewed Bush's weekend summit proposals
as an important first step in integrating the Soviets into the
global economic system.
   But they cautioned against looking for any big, immediate payoff
in terms of expanding Soviet trade or boosting Soviet living
standards.
   ``The Soviet economy is in very bad shape. The question is,
`Will this rouse that economy?' I am skeptical,'' said Marshall
Goldman, a Harvard professor and leading expert on the Soviet Union.
   ``The situaion is deteriorating in the Soviet Union,'' he said.
``You have got to turn around and show concrete results that will
end up on the table and that is just not happening.''
   In many ways, the Soviet economy is facing more dire problems
now than before Gorbachev launched his ``perestroika''
restructuring reforms. With winter approaching, the country is
plagued by strikes and severe shortages of many consumer items.
   Bush's economic proposals include:
   _Immediate start to negotiating a U.S.-Soviet trade agreement
with a goal of completion by June's planned summit in Washington
between the two leaders. That would also be the target for lifting
the 15-year-old high tariffs on Soviet goods imposed under the
Jackson-Vanik amendment that penalized the Soviets for their
restrictive emigration policies.
   _U.S. support for granting the Soviets observer status in the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the 97-country organization
that regulates world trade. The United States had previously
opposed Soviet requests for observer status in GATT, arguing that
the Soviet system was incompatible with GATT's free-trade
principles.
   _Recommendations that Congress lift a ban on providing trade
credits to the Soviet Union through the U.S. Export-Import Bank.
   _Negotiations leading to a U.S.-Soviet treaty that would
facilitate U.S. investments in the Soviet Union.
   While the proposals announced in Malta appear modest, economists
said they allowed Gorbachev to return to his own country with
symbolic victories showing concrete evidence of the Bush
administration's support for perestroika.
   ``This is a foot in the door for the Soviet Union,'' said Howard
Wachtel, an economics professor at American University. ``It sets
in motion a train of activity which had largely been cut off by
Stalin when he opted not to participate in Western economic
organizations after World War II.''
   In addition to observer status in GATT, the Soviets are
considering seeking admission to the International Monetary Fund
and the World Bank. Admission in those organizations, still
considered to be far in the future, would open up a substantial
borrowing pool the Soviets could tap to support their economy.
   Bush seemed to be seeking to play down expectations for
immediate payoffs.
   In a news conference Monday in Brussels, Bush said the chances
Gorbachev would be allowed to participate in next year's economic
summit with the West's seven leading industrial countries were
``slim and none.''
   But Bush said his initiatives would help provide the Soviets
with important expertise on how market-based economies work.
   Dwayne O. Andreas, chief executive of the agricultural giant,
Archer-Daniels-Midland Co. of Decatur, Ill., said the lifting of
the high tariffs on Soviet products would allow the Soviets to sell
more goods here and should foster reciprocal actions by the Soviets
to purchase more American goods, particularly agricultural products.
   ``Unleashing the forces of free-enterprise (in the Soviet Union)
can't be anything but beneficial'' to prospects for world peace,
Andreas said.
   U.S. sales to the Soviet Union have totaled $3.22 billion so far
this year, primarily in agricultural products, while Soviet sales
in this country total $555 million.
   Economists said the summit agreements were not likely to boost
that total quickly although they saw opportunities for increasing
sales of such consumer items as vodka and Soviet furs.
   ``The Soviets don't have the money to buy a lot more in terms of
imports and they don't have all that much to export,'' said David
Wyss, chief financial economist for DRI-McGraw Hill.
   But Allen Sinai, chief economist at the Boston Co., said it
would be wrong to judge the Malta summit a failure if it does not
produce quick economic results.
   ``Malta is a long-run affair with all kinds of great promise,''
he said. ``One should be cautious, but there are great hopes and
optimism that a new era is dawning.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
