<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     12-05 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against all major foreign
currencies except the Canadian dollar today in thin European
trading, currency dealers said.
   Gold prices fell in Europe as much as $6.25 a troy ounce,
continuing a sharp decline on profit-taking, bullion dealers said.
   Markets were slowing as the year end approaches, with many
dealers saying they were unwilling to take positions which could
affect their profits or increase losses.
   ``It's getting very thin,'' a Frankfurt trader said. ``A lot of
banks are just stopping. It's getting very boring.''
   Toru Kanai, a currency analyst with New Japan Securities, Co.
said earlier trading in Tokyo was also quiet.
   ``Trading was very boring, and there is no news until Friday,
when the U.S. unemployment figures for November come out,'' he said.
   The markets hope the unemployment data will give an indication
of what the Federal Reserve's monetary policy will be, traders said.
   ``It's all a problem of interest rates and right now there's no
clear indication from the Fed,'' said a Milan trader.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.20 yen to a closing 143.68 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at a higher rate of 143.70 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.7850 West German marks, up from 1.7808; 1.6050
Swiss francs, up from 1.5995; 6.0945 French francs, up from 6.0800;
2.0137 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0095; 1,314.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,312.00; 1.1635 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1640.
   In London, the dollar rose slightly against the British pound.
It cost $1.5636 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5638 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $402.35 a troy ounce,
down from $406.25 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $402.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $401.75, down from $408 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $6.45 to close at a bid $402.86.
   Silver fell in London to a bid price of $5.54 a troy ounce from
Monday's $5.60.
</TEXT>
