<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 0739EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     12-05 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Hit New High, Dollar Closes Higher in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index climbed to a
new high closing for the ninth time in 10 trading days today, while
the dollar edged up against the Japanese yen for the third
consecutive trading day.
   The dollar closed at 143.68 yen, up 0.20 yen from Monday's
143.48-yen finish. It opened at 143.70 yen and stayed in a narrow
range between 143.67 yen and 143.85 yen. The dollar now has gained
0.78 yen in three trading days.
   ``Today's trading was extremely thin,'' said a trader with
Mitsubishi Bank in Tokyo. Spot trading volume totaled $4.1 billion
as most market players remained on the sidelines awaiting the
release Friday of data on U.S. unemployment in November, he added.
   ``There was no major movement, although the fluctuation was kind
of nervous,'' he said on condition of anonymity.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues rose 190.30 points, or 0.51 percent, closing at 37,494.17.
The previous record of 37,303.87 was set Monday, when the index
climbed 171.19 points.
   In the last 10 trading days, the only pause in the succession of
record high closings for the index came Friday, when it declined
slightly after a seven-day climb.
   Stability on the foreign exchange market and expectations for
lower domestic short-term interest rates encouraged investors
today, dealers said.
   Yutaka Yoshino, a dealer with Nikko Securities Co., said,
``Today's dealings followed an uptrend from yesterday, when market
players believed East-West tensions had ended as a result of the
U.S.-Soviet summit meeting over the weekend.''
   Japanese investors see this relaxation as likely to provide new
business opportunities, he said.
   Institutional investors also were buying in efforts to wrap up
the year with increased profits, he added.
   Some investors were selling to take profits because of concern
over the speed of the index's rise, but this was more than offset
by buying based on optimism concerning interest rates and business
opportunities in the Eastern bloc, Yoshino said.
   An estimated 1.3 billion shares changed hands on the first
section, up from 1.2 billion the previous day. Among gainers were
steel, shipbuilding and electrical issues.
</TEXT>
