<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   12-05 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybeans Bounce Back from Monday's Losses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened higher in quiet
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Prices across the board were expected to bounce back from
yesterday's selloff, with corn leading the way because of higher
than expected weekly export inspections. The inspections are an
indication of the amount of grain ready for export.
   There was an expectation that current corn prices could generate
additional export demand, said analyst Joel Karlin of Research
Department Inc.
   Wheat futures were higher following yesterday's announcement of
wheat purchases by the Soviet Union and Iraq.
   Continued dry conditions in winter wheat crop areas also was
expected to boost prices. Private forecasters on Monday had
predicted rain for the area.
   Soybean prices were expected to pressured by reports the weather
in South America is favorable to soybean development.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to { cent higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.04\ a bushel; corn was \
cent to 1 cent higher with December at $2.33{ a bushel; oats were \
cent to { cent higher with December at $1.43{ a bushel; soybeans
were \ cent to 1{ cents higher with January at $5.73} a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Pork futures received a boost from projections for mostly stable
wholesale pork product prices.
   Livestock futures were lifted by slightly higher prices paid for
boxed beef.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .18 cent higher with December at
75.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .22 cent higher
with January at 82.85 cents a pound; hogs were .03 cent to .45 cent
higher with December at 50.90 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .08 cent to .30 cent higher with February at 56 cents a pound.
   Livestock futures settled higher and pork futures lower in
Monday's trading.
</TEXT>
