<FIRST>u f AM-ChristmasClubs Bjt   12-05 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Christmas Clubs, Bjt,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Savers Saying `Bah Humbug' To Christmas Clubs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: McLoughlin cq in 19th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Once a popular way of saving for the holidays, today's
``Christmas Clubs'' have gone the way of the one-horse open sleigh
in the sophisticated world of investments.
   The prevalence of savings products with more generous yields and
widespread reliance on credit cards have dampened many depositors'
desires to open up these traditional accounts.
   Many banks and thrifts also have stopped offering Christmas
Clubs because they've become too costly to maintain, while those
that still offer them no longer advertise to promote the service.
   Between 55 percent and 60 percent of the nation's credit unions,
though, still offer holiday clubs.
   ``We like to say that they're a fully matured product,'' said
Richard Arnold, national sales manager at Christmas Club A Corp.,
which created the concept in 1910, when a Carlisle, Pa., bank
organized a holiday savings program for schoolchildren.
   Even the Easton, Pa., company, which still markets club coupon
booklets to about 5,000 financial institutions nationwide, has been
shifting away from its namesake, printing everything from
tax-collection booklets for state governments to bill-payment
booklets for cable television.
   An estimated 23 million Americans hold some type of holiday
savings account, a number that has held relatively steady for a
number of years, according to Christmas Club A Corp. The average
annual savings total runs between $300 and $400.
   Christmas Clubs generally attract customers who can't afford
savings accounts that may require a minimum balance, or who need
the discipline of a forced savings plan. Many banks see holiday
accounts more as a service to their customer than a money maker.
   These clubs usually start in the fall, just as the holiday
season is about to begin and when many consumers realize they
should have saved more for gifts, and are aimed at accumulating
money for the following Christmas. Clubs typically permit weekly
deposits of as little as $5. Although there are no fees, early
withdrawal or failure to meet the deposit schedule may result in
interest penalties.
   Many banks have dropped coupon payment books, long associated
with these accounts, in favor of less costly electronic fund
transfers, which take an automatic deduction from checking or
savings.
   Either way, the returns on holiday clubs may conjure up more
images of Scrooge than Santa Claus.
   Some institutions don't even provide interest, offering instead
a stuffed animal, Christmas tree ornament or other premium when an
account is opened.
   For clubs that do pay interest, yields run slightly lower or
about the same as those on passbook savings accounts, which average
5.17 percent nationwide, or statement savings accounts, which
average 5.22 percent, according to Bank Rate Monitor, a North Palm
Beach, Fla.-based newsletter. Credit unions often pay slightly
higher rates on holiday club accounts than do banks and thrifts.
   But a more sophisticated investor with the self-discipline to
regularly put away money _ rather than running up credit card
balances _ can do better elsewhere.
   A $1,000 annual deposit in a Christmas Club would yield an
average $51.70. The same $1,000 invested in a one-year certificate
of deposit yielding 8.12 percent simple interest would earn $81.20,
according to Bank Rate Monitor.
   Bank deregulation, which marks its seventh anniversary
Wednesday, helped make Christmas Clubs less attractive because it
enabled financial institutions to offer more competitive, higher
yields on a wider variety of investment products, such as CDs or
money market accounts.
   ``Before deregulation ... when all banks and thrifts paid the
same rates on passbook accounts Christmas Clubs were annual
re-inventions of the wheel,'' said Robert K. Heady, Bank Rate
Monitor's publisher. ``Today, Santa is almost absent from bank
ads.''
   At Chemical Bank in New York, where only 1,000 of its depositors
have holiday club accounts, some branches don't even mention that
Christmas Clubs are available.
   ``There are certain branches where it's much more popular than
others. And those people will put up a very modest sign saying,
`Yes, we have holiday clubs,''' said Susan McLoughlin, assistant
vice president of Chemical's deposit products group.
   A recent study for Christmas Club A Corp. indicated a majority
of the holiday club savers kept up their accounts almost out of
routine, or else loyalty to their banks.
   Nearly half of those surveyed said they wouldn't search for
another financial institution to open a Christmas Club account if
theirs discontinued them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
