<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   12-05 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks ended higher in thin trading on London's
Stock Exchange Tuesday, boosted by strength in the property sector,
some healthy earnings reports and a stronger pound.
   ``There is a continuation of the bullish sentiment we saw last
week, although it wasn't a particularly busy day,'' one dealer said.
   By the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 24.1 points, or 1.05 percent, at 2,327.5, well above its
early morning low of 2,301.2.
   The Financial Times 30-share index ended 13.8 points higher at
1,836.8. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 11.60 points to
close at 1,265.88.
   Volume totaled 428.5 million shares, down from 484.4 million
shares Monday.
   After a weak opening, shares rose on news that British Land PLC,
Britain's third largest property company, suspended trading of its
shares at 359 pence ($5.60) pending an announcement Wednesday that
involves proposals to maximize shareholder value. Traders
speculated the company may announce the sale of property.
   The news strengthened the property sector, recently the focus of
bearish sentiment because of Britain's high interest rates and
slowing economy.
</TEXT>
