<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     12-05 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Sag</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell today after a morning rally
fizzled amid profit-taking and investor confusion about the
direction of the economy, analysts said.
   Strength in the high technology sector helped pull the market
higher in early dealings after International Business Machines
Corp. announced a major restructuring. IBM said it planned a $4
billion share buyback, a cutback of 10,000 jobs and a
fourth-quarter charge of $2.3 billion.
   ``IBM is the highlight of the day,'' said Emmanuel Geronimous,
senior vice president at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Takeover speculation also helped fuel early gains in other
blue-chip issues, including transportation stocks.
   But the blue-chip rally fizzled as the broader market lagged.
Stock prices retreated amid profit-taking as investors took
advantage of the market's recent gains, traders said.
   ``That's bound to happen. The market was going up with no real
conviction,'' said Charles Jensen, chief technical analyst for MKI
Securities Corp.
   Wall Street analysts said investor uncertainty about the economy
and interest rates remained in the background helping depress
prices ahead of Friday's report on November unemployment. Recent
economic data has pointed to a slowdown in economic growth.
   Observers say stock investors are hoping the unemployment data
confirms the slow-growth scenario and prompts the Federal Reserve
to take steps to lower interest rates to stimulate economic growth
and corporate earnings in 1990.
</TEXT>
