<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     12-05 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petroleum Futures Firmer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices rose in uneventful trading
Tuesday with refined petroleum products posting the biggest gains.
   Demand for wholesale home heating oil has risen lately as the
temperatures have declined in many parts of the country.
   The contract for January delivery of wholesale No.2 heating oil
rose 0.26 cent to 64.05 cents a gallon on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, adding to Monday's increase of 0.88 cent. Contracts for
delivery through April rose by 0.21 cent to 0.29 cent.
   Among other refined products traded on the New York Merc,
wholesale unleaded gasoline for January delivery closed 0.32 cent
higher at 52.84 after adding 0.41 cent on Monday. Later contracts
ended with similarly sized gains.
   The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the main grade
of U.S. crude oil, rebounded 9 cents to close at $20.34 per
42-gallon barrel. On Monday the contract had fallen 5 cents. The
February through April contracts finished with slightly larger
increases.
   Energy analysts said there was no market-moving news and trading
volume was light to moderate. Traders continued to buy heating oil
on the assumption that cold weather around the United States and
shortages in Europe would boost demand.
   Analyst William Byers of Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. said traders were
reluctant to establish significant new holdings ahead of the
American Petroleum Institute's weekly statistics, which were
released after the market closed.
   He said the API reported a surprisingly large buildup in crude
oil stocks but inventories of refined products were in line with
expectations.
</TEXT>
