<DOCNO> AP891205-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 1935EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Grain-China     12-05 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-China,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Million Tons Authorized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has been authorized to buy an additional
1 million metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices, the
Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   Acting Undersecretary John B. Campbell said the wheat will be
available to China under the department's Export Enhancement
Program, or EEP. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to
36.7 bushels of wheat.
   Under EEP arrangements, private exporters can sell U.S.
commodities at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in
selected overseas markets and then collect free government
surpluses of grain or other commodities as subsidy.
   The subsidies have averaged from around $10 per ton, to more
than $40 per ton of wheat, or in the range of 27 cents to about
$1.10 per bushel.
   Campbell said 10,000 tons remained in the previous EEP
allocation for China announced last Feb. 27. That allocation was
for 2 million tons.
   China was the largest foreign buyer of U.S. wheat in the 1988-89
wheat marketing year that ended last May 31 with orders for nearly
8.1 million tons, all of it under the EEP program.
   Sales for 1989-90 total about 4.7 million tons, most of it
without subsidies.
   China is also the world's largest wheat producer this year with
an output estimated at 91 million tons. That compares with the
Soviet Union's harvest of 89 million tons this year and the U.S.
production of about 56 million tons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
