<DOCNO> AP891205-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 1726EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Mellon-Meritor     12-05 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mellon-Meritor,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mellon Buys 54 PSFS Branches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mellon Bank Corp., continuing its rebound
from hard financial times, said Tuesday it had agreed to pay buy 54
local branches of PSFS, the nation's oldest mutual savings bank.
   Meritor Savings Bank, which owns PSFS, is expected to get about
$335 million from Mellon for the branches. The move is the latest
in an asset-paring restructuring that Meritor started in 1987.
   The purchase will more than double Mellon's deposits in the
Philadelphia area to about $8.4 million, or 14.3 percent of the
market. CoreStates will lead the market with $8.99 million in
deposits upon completion of its purchase of First Pennsylvania,
expected in March.
   ``My guess is the Philadelphia market will go through more
consolidation. This puts us in a much more viable position,'' said
Frank V. Cahouet, chairman and chief executive of Mellon.
   Meritor's board approved the agreement at a meeting Monday,
Mellon officials said.
   Cahouet said the deal fits Mellon's strategy of increasing its
retail business. The Meritor branches will increase Mellon's retail
deposits by 36 percent to $19.588 billion.
   ``I'm glad to see Mellon thinks it's gotten out of the
turn-around, clean-up phase and is looking to expand,'' said
Kenneth F. Puglisi, a stock market analyst at Keefe, Bruyette &amp;
Woods.
   Last year, Mellon lost $65 million, or $3.65 per share. In 1987,
Mellon lost $844 million, or $31.19 per share, largely because of
provisions to cover bad loans to developing nations and the
slumping U.S. oil patch region.
   In the first nine months of this year, Mellon netted $204
million.
   Mellon said it expects to finance the purchase by issuing a
combination of common stock, preferred stock and debt in roughly
equal amounts. Cahouet said the bank is exploring its financing
options and the stock and debt issues are the most ``pessimistic or
conservative'' scenario.
   After the transaction is completed, Mellon's Philadelphia
subsidiary, Mellon Bank (East), plans to change its name to
``Mellon PSFS'' and plans to operate all its Philadelphia area
branches under that name, Mellon said.
   Mellon already has 66 branches in Philadelphia and suburban
counties. It will consider closing branches were there is
duplication but hasn't made any firm decisions, said Thomas F.
Donovan, chairman and chief executive of Mellon Bank (East).
   Donovan said normal attrition should cover any jobs lost in the
transaction. About 750 employees are expected to move from PSFS to
Mellon PSFS.
   ``We are constantly moving and shifting to see how best to
address the marketplace. It is very important to us to increase
market share in this area. Retail banking is very important to
Mellon,'' Cahouet said.
   The deal leaves Meritor with 29 branches, nearly all of them in
Philadelphia. The remaining branches will change their name to The
Philadelphia Savings Fund Society.
   Meritor, which hasn't seen an annual profit since 1986 and lost
$12.8 million in the third quarter of this year, has been paring
its operations in a restructuring effort that started in October
1987.
   Once the deal with Mellon is complete, Meritor's assets will
have dropped from a June 1987 high of $20.2 billion to about $8
billion, said Meritor spokesman Joseph M. Barrett.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
