<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-05 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Declines; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BC-LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar declined against most major
currencies Tuesday in quiet, featureless trading.
   Gold prices finished higher in the United States after falling
overseas. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a troy ounce of
gold bullion at $403.50 as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $401.20 late
Monday.
   Dealers said the foreign-exchange market was uninspired because
of a lack of news or new economic indicators after the recent surge
in the West German mark. They predicted little change for the rest
of this week.
   ``It's very much a holiday market,'' said Jeff Mondschein,
manager of foreign-exchange trading at Continental Illinois
National Bank &amp; Trust Co. in Chicago.
   Currency dealers overseas are said to be closing out trading
positions before the year end. Market volume tends to dry up toward
the end of the year, when dealers are hesitant to risk profits or
add to losses.
   Mondschein said traders are awaiting Friday's government report
on unemployment in November for an indication of U.S. economic
growth.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar finished at 143.68 Japanese yen, up from 143.48
yen on Monday. Later, in London, the dollar rose to 143.77 yen. By
the end of the trading day in New York, the dollar was quoted at
143.70 yen, up from 143.65 yen late Monday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.5715, more expensive for
buyers than late Monday's $1.5638. Later, in New York, a pound
fetched $1.5700, up from $1.5622 late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.7775 West German marks, down from 1.7842; 1.5915
Swiss francs, down from 1.6065; 6.0670 French francs, down from
6.0915; 1,309.00 Italian lire, down from 1,314.50; and 1.1630
Canadian dollars, down from 1.1636.
   Dealers in Frankfurt said the mark should remain strong because
employment in West Germany in October reached 27.9 million, up
25,000 from September and the highest level in the republic's
40-year history.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.7790 West German marks, down from 1.7808; 1.5910
Swiss francs, down from 1.5995; 6.0675 French francs, down from
6.0800; 2.0100 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0095; 1,307.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,312.00; 1.1640 Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   Gold closed in London at a bid price of $404 a troy ounce, down
from $406.25 on Monday. The closing bid price in Zurich,
Switzerland, was $403.50, down from $408.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $402.95 bid, down from
$409.45.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery
closed at $403.50 a troy ounce, up from $401.10 late Monday.
   Silver closed in London at a bid price of $5.60 a troy ounce,
unchanged.
   On New York's Comex, silver for current delivery closed at
$5.533 a troy ounce, up from $5.509 late Monday.
</TEXT>
