<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 1738EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-05 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lack of Demand Sends Copper Lower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices fell sharply Tuesday on New York's
Commodity Exchange as traders reacted to a downturn in demand for
the metal.
   In other markets, precious metal futures rebounded from Monday's
selloff, grain and soybeans futures were higher, while livestock
futures gained, hog futures closed mixed and energy futures climbed.
   Copper settled 1.35 cents to 2.40 cents lower with the contract
for delivery in December at $1.0620 a pound.
   Copper prices plunged at the opening bell and continued under
pressure throughout the day as traders failed to hold support
levels.
   Analyst Don Tierney of Stanley Bell &amp; Co. in New York said
consumption of copper is declining because of the softening
economic climate.
   Precious metal futures rebounded on the Comex as traders
operated on the belief that Monday's sharp decline was overdone,
Tierney said.
   Helping gold and silver prices was the weakening of the U.S.
dollar against the Swiss franc and the West German mark
   The advance also was helped by short-covering by European
investors who sold the market Monday.
   Gold was $2 to $2.40 higher with December at $403.50 a troy
ounce; silver was 2.4 cent to 3.5 cent higher wtih December at
$5.533 a troy ounce.
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly higher in modest trading
on the Chicago Board of Trade as the market recovered some losses
sustained in the previous session.
   Corn futures led the trend upward in the aftermath of Monday's
U.S. Department of Agriculture weekly export inspections report,
which was higher than expected, said analyst Dale Gustafson of
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   The inspections tally of 79 million bushels was well above trade
estimates for 67 million to 73 million. The inspections are an
indication of the amount of grain ready for export.
   Nearby wheat prices were lower, but the new crop futures gained
on reports that weather conditions in the winter wheat crop areas
continue on the dry side.
   Soybean futures trading continues sluggish, as a lack of export
sales dampens the market. Soybean prices also were pressured by
reports the weather in South America is favorable to soybean
development.
   Wheat was 1{ cent lower to 1{ cents higher with December at
$4.02{ a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 2{ cents higher with December
at $2.34{ cents a bushel; oats were a 1 cent to 2\ cents higher
with December at $1.44\ a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents to 3{
cents higher with January at $5.75 cents a bushel.
   Livestock futures were higher and pork futures mixed on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Hog futures were lifted by firm cash prices, said analyst Tom
Morgan of Sterling Research Corp. in Arlington Heights, Ill. He
noted that pork bellies futures were pushed lower by concern over
the large levels of bellies moving into storage.
   Concern over a cold snap in the northern plains, which could
adversely affect feeding operations, helped to send livestock
futures higher, Morgan said.
   Prices also were helped by news the Soviet Union may be
interested in buying U.S. beef.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .35 cent higher with December at
75.57 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .35 cent higher
with January at 82.97 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .70 cent
higher with December at 51.22 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .22 cent to .70 cent lower with February at 55.15 cents a
pound.
   Energy futures were higher in moderate trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   There was little news to influence prices, and traders awaited
the release of American Petroleum Institute inventory figures, said
analyst Peter Beutel of Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
   API figures released after the close of trading, showed crude
oil stocks up 8.45 million barrels in the latest week and refined
product stocks up 2.89 million barrels.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 4 cents to 12 cents higher
with January at $20.34 cents a barrel; heating oil was .21 cent to
.29 cent higher with January at 64.05 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .28 cent to .44 cent higher with January at 52.84
cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
