<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesProbe     12-05 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Probe,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Live Hog Trading Now Under Federal Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected violations in live hog futures trading
at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange are the latest focus of a
federal probe of the nation's largest commodities exchanges, a
newspaper reported Tuesday.
   Federal investigators have issued subpoenas to as many as seven
hog futures traders, the Chicago Sun-Times reported, citing
unidentified Merc members and attorneys.
   At least one of the traders had been questioned about suspected
trading violations that occurred as long ago as 1982, the newspaper
said.
   Ira Raphaelson, acting U.S. attorney, declined to comment
Tuesday on the report.
   Merc spokesman Andrew Yemma also declined comment.
   The federal investigation, which became known to the public in
January, initially focused on trading in the Merc's Japanese yen
and Swiss franc pits, and on trading in the soybean and U.S.
Treasury bond pits of the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The probe has so far resulted in the indictment of 47 traders
and one clerk. Of those, 14 people have pleaded guilty.
   Last week, in the first known expansion of the investigation out
of the four initial pits, at least nine traders in the Merc's
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 futures pit were subpoenaed to testify before
a federal grand jury.
   The live hog futures trading pit is the smallest of the pits so
far affected by the investigation. It draws only 40 or 50 traders
on a busy day _ less than a tenth as many as some of the more
active pits.
</TEXT>
