<SECOND>AM-Great Northern, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0165,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia-Pacific Extends Offer To Buy Great Northern Until Dec. 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Great Northern filing
court papers seeking to block Georgia-Pacific's court moves.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp. extended its $3.6 billion
offer to buy rival paper-maker Great Northern Nekoosa Corp. for one
week Tuesday, but officials of the target remained opposed to the
deal.
   The $63-a-share bid, originally set to expire at midnight EST
Monday, was extended by Georgia-Pacific until midnight Dec. 11.
   ``We feel, as we announced previously, that consummation of the
merger ... would violate applicable antitrust laws,'' said Great
Northern spokesman Stephen Hill.
   Officials of Norwalk, Conn.-based Great Northern have refused to
discuss the proposed merger with Georgia-Pacific, though the
chairman of the Atlanta company said Great Northern shareholders
already have indicated they favor the takeover.
   Georgia-Pacific Chairman T. Marshall Hahn said 32.3 million
shares of Great Northern stock already have been tendered since his
company made the takeover bid, representing nearly 59 percent of
total shares outstanding.
   ``That is a very substantial percentage, and we believe the
shareholders are sending the clear message to Great Northern's
board and management that they want our offer to be accepted,''
Hahn said.
   Hill said Great Northern did not view the tender in the same
light. ``As you know, people could withdraw that at any time,'' he
said.
   Great Northern stock was up 25 cents a share to $61.62{ in early
New York Stock Exchange trading Tuesday.
   Chad E. Brown, an industry analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. in New York, said Georgia-Pacific had no choice at this time
but to extend the offer.
   He noted that a number of matters _ Justice Department
clearance, a legal challenge to Maine's corporate takeover statute
and a challenge to Great Northern's anti-takeover provisions _ must
be resolved before Georgia-Pacific can proceed with the proposed
acquisition.
   ``Certain conditions hadn't been met,'' Brown said. ``The choice
was to withdraw and let it (the offer) expire. And that's not a
choice.''
   He said it is possible that the offer will be extended again
Dec. 11.
   Atlanta-based Georgia-Pacific raised its offer from $58 a share
to $63 Nov. 19 after Great Northern's board rejected the original
Oct. 31 offer.
   Georgia-Pacific, meanwhile, filed a motion late Monday in U.S.
District Court in Portland, Maine, asking for a ruling in its
lawsuit challenging the ``poison pill'' anti-takeover provisions of
Great Northern's bylaws. Great Northern is incorporated in Maine.
   Georgia-Pacific said the poison pill violates the Maine Business
Corporation Act because it lets owners of stock in takeover targets
_ except for the hostile suitor _ buy moreshares at a 50 percent
discount.
   Great Northern filed an objection Tuesday to Georgia-Pacific's
request for a temporary restraining order and preliminary
injunction.
   Georgia-Pacific wants to stop Great Northern from changing its
financial structure to make itself more difficult to acquire,
unless it provides 72 hours notice, and also wants to move up a
shareholders meeting from March to within 30 days so shareholders
can vote quickly on the tender offer.
   Great Northern says Georgia-Pacific has shown no good reason to
move the meeting up, and it has said the 72-hour notice would not
give its directors enough flexibility to manage the company's
affairs.
   Great Northern had sales of $3.6 billion in 1988 from its paper
pulp, box, lumber and plywood operations. Georgia-Pacific had $9.5
billion in sales.
</TEXT>
