<HEAD>Dollar Firm, Stock Prices Fall in Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar remained firm in early trading
against the Japanese yen Wednesday morning, while share prices on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell moderately.
   The dollar started trading at 143.72 yen, up 0.04 yen from
Tuesday's close here of 143.68 yen. It hardly budged from it close
of 143.73 yen overnight in New York.
   A dealer with the Bank of Tokyo said the dollar-yen exchange
rate remained in a narrow range because of a lack of fresh
market-affecting news.
   Many market players are awaiting the release of U.S.
unemployment figures for November, due out Friday in Washington,
said the dealer, who spoke anonymously.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which gained 190.30 points for a new high Tuesday, shed
139.15 points, or 0.37 percent, shortly after the market opened to
move to 37,355.02.
